<HEAD>Italians Pray for Rain In Drought-Stricken Areas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of people prayed for rain in northern Italian churches and some parched communities planned religious processions, hoping to bring an end to one of the worst droughts in years. At 1,300 Roman Catholic churches in the diocese of <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> on Sunday, priests invoked `` the rain that restores the earth and air,'' according to the diocese. Churchgoers in <LOCATION> Bergamo </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Genoa </ORGANIZATION> have also been praying for rain as sunny, dry weather threatens crops and left ski slopes bare. Several parishes in small towns south of <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> were planning processions along the Adda river if rain did not arrive in the next few days, the Italian news agency <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> has received only half the precipitation it usually gets in the September-January period. The <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> area has had one rain shower since November 24, while <ORGANIZATION> Genoa </ORGANIZATION> has been dry for four months. The lack of rain has prompted limits on private water use and contributed to brush fires that have scorched thousands of acres in northern <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. The dry weather is the result of a high-pressure system that has remained over the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> for months, meteorologists say.
