<FIRST>r i PM-Jamaica-Election     02-13 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jamaica-Election,0792</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Image for Jamaica and Michael Manley</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In returning <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> to power, <PERSON> Jamaicans </PERSON> opted for a new style of leadership, decisively rejecting the tough economic solutions and autocratic demeanor of conservative incumbent <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON>. The island also emerged from its short but tense election campaign with an improved record on controlling political violence. Preliminary indications were that the charismatic <PERSON> Manley </PERSON>, a radical-turned-moderate leader with a new pro-business image, won 44 of 60 seats in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in Thursday's voting. <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>'s leading political analyst and pollster, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indies </ORGANIZATION>, said he thought there would be no fundamental policy shifts under <PERSON> Manley </PERSON>, who was prime minister from 1972 to 1980. `` There will be the same policies, but a different style of leadership,'' <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> said. `` He really feels obsessed with correcting his mismanagement during the 1970s.'' <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON>, a technocrat and hard-nosed manager, was regarded as a friend of big business, which is wary of <LOCATION> Manley </LOCATION>. `` There definitely are going to be memories of what happened in the past,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Thwaites </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Private </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sector </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, the country's main business group. But he said if <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> carries out his current proposals, `` there will be very little change in the economic policies of the country.'' <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> appropriated private farms and heavily taxed business during his previous government. Now, he says he has `` abandoned all thoughts of nationalization'' and wants to give private enterprise a free hand in developing the economy. <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON> improved the island's economy, especially tourism, but he did it by doubling the foreign debt to about $ 4 billion, raising taxes, laying off thousands of workers and cutting back spending on health and education. Prices rose sharply, leading to food riots in 1985. `` The program he -LRB- <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON> -RRB- has carried out has been very rigid,'' said Stone. `` And he's paying the price for it.'' <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON>, a staunch ally of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and close political friend of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, said he was afraid the results of his economic measures had not reached enough people. `` You see the results, yes, but the results have not reached enough people, -LRB- so -RRB- that enough people will say ` Yes, well, we took the medicine and we've benefited,''' he said recently. He said he was forced to take unpopular measures because of the near-bankrupt state of the economy when he took office in 1980 after eight years of <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> rule and the collapse of the bauxite industry in 1983. He said younger voters had no memories of how bad things were under <PERSON> Manley </PERSON>. <PERSON> Manley </PERSON>, known by his most ardent supporters as `` <PERSON> Joshua </PERSON>'' after the Old Testament prophet, pledged to revitalize schools and hospitals he said were neglected for eight years under <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON>'s cost-cutting administration As prime minister, <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> gained an international reputation as a firebrand socialist. He forged close ties with <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> and brought in scores of <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> doctors and technicians. In recent years, he has turned sharply to the political center as a social democrat. The 64-year-old leader has been saying he is an older and wiser man, and on election night Thursday he thanked the <LOCATION> Jamaican </LOCATION> people for giving him a `` second chance.'' <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> said he would restore relations with <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> but was more interested in working with the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration and Western lending institutions such as the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. He said his first foreign trip as prime minister will be to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to establish `` the widest and most constructive'' relationship possible with the new administration. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration wo n't be pleased that <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> is reopening the <ORGANIZATION> Cuban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, which was closed by <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON>, but <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say they are encouraged by <PERSON> Manley </PERSON>'s pledge to limit the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> presence and influence to formal diplomatic ties. Policy issues were overshadowed during the campaign by fears that bloodshed among rival political supporters would further split the nation of 2.4 million and wreck tourism, which brings in $ 600 million a year and is <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>'s top earner of foreign exchange. The tourism industry still is recovering from a sharp drop in visitors in the aftermath of Hurricane Gilbert, which slammed into the island Sept. 12, killing 45 people and causing $ 1 billion in damage. In 1980, when <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>'s last nationally contested election was held, an estimated 700 people were murdered over a nine-month campaign. This time, 13 died in campaign-related shootings and stabbings. But in comparison with the mayhem of 1980, the election appeared to mark a turning point in Jamaican politics.
