<FIRST>r i PM-Paraguay-Adjusting     02-13 0867</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay-Adjusting,0896</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paraguayans Adjust To Political Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The gunfire has stopped, the dictator is gone and the celebrating is over. Paraguayans now must get down to the business of adjusting to life without the only president most of them have ever known. On the surface, the future looks brighter for this South American nation of nearly 4 million _ holding promises of new leadership and perhaps a more representative government. The likelihood that another general will replace ousted leader Gen. <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, now in exile in neighboring <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, bothers few Paraguayans. Neither does the certainty that political power will remain in the hands of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, a pillar of <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s support throughout his nearly 35 years in power `` It does n't make any difference what kind of government we get, it has to be better than the one we had,'' said 20-year-old <PERSON> Celso </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, one of the thousands of citizens who went into the street to celebrate the fall of the 76-year-old dictator. Gen. <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, whose tanks and troops ousted <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> in a violent coup Feb. 3, seems to be many things his predecessor was not. <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> quickly dissolved <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and called for elections May 1 in which all parties _ except the Communists _ can participate. He promised to respect human rights, freedom of expression and the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. He named an 11-man Cabinet that even opposition members grudgingly admit includes <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>'s most successful and talented administrators and technocrats. The new government will have to deal with urgent problems, including poverty, economic stagnation, 30 percent annual inflation and a foreign debt of nearly $ 2 billion. The church, which had become a leading opposition body in this predominantly Roman Catholic nation, promised the new president its support. <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, 65, has denied rumors he may be linked to drug traffickers who move cocaine through <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>, and he pledged to cooperate with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and international agencies seeking to end the drug trade. In <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>'s first presidential press conference, the affable, self-assured cavalry general left open the possibility he may run for president. `` I am simply a soldier, not a politician,'' <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> told reporters. `` However, if I can be useful to my country, I will do what I am asked.'' <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Argana </PERSON>, the new foreign minister who was seen as the party's most likely presidential choice, quickly denied reports he would run and endorsed <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which claims membership of 1.4 million and has ruled since 1947, has said it will call a convention soon to select candidates and new party leaders. The 101-year-old party was badly split in August 1987 when a small but fanatical pro-Stroessner group usurped party leadership in a battle over how to prepare for post-Stroessner rule. The <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> backers, an inner circle of militant government and party officials, favored continuation of hard-line authoritarian rule, possibly under <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s eldest son, <PERSON> Gustavo </PERSON>, an air force colonel. The majority, calling themselves `` traditionalists,'' favored some relaxation of iron rule and the eventual replacement of <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> with a civilian president. Recently, the situation was complicated by <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s failing health. The nation, accustomed to seeing his picture every day in the newspapers, was astounded in September when he vanished for two weeks for an unannounced prostate operation. In a nation where virtually every decision was made by the president, the wheels of government ground to a halt. `` The president used to personally sign most government documents,'' said a foreign diplomat. `` Some of our transferring personnel even received shipment orders for their household goods signed by him.'' <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>'s decision to act, diplomats and politicians say, came when <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> ordered him to give up command of the powerful <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> and retire, or accept a political post, possibly defense minister, without command of troops. <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s downfall sent citizens _ 70 percent of whom had known only <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> as president _ into the streets to celebrate. Rival politicians, bitter enemies for years, embraced, danced and sang. The nation's opposition political parties face new problems. Most were unrecognized because they had not been allowed to participate in the political process. `` The hinges of our political limbs are rusty from lack of use,'' said <PERSON> Euclides </PERSON> <PERSON> Acevedo </PERSON>, president of the left-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Febrerista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> <PERSON> Laino </PERSON>, popular head of the National Accord, a loose grouping of four opposition parties, suggested the opposition needs `` as much as a year'' to organize to effectively compete with the <ORGANIZATION> Colorados </ORGANIZATION> in elections. Political leaders largely discount the possibility that <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> or his son <PERSON> Gustavo </PERSON> could effectively organiize any effort to return to power. <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> supporters were hard to find after the coup and they spoke with reluctance. `` I have to admit that I do n't think that <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> was all bad,'' said a taxi driver as he drove through streets of happy demonstrators following the coup. `` He gave us peace and he built schools for our children and roads where there were only mudholes before.'' `` Look at those people,'' he said, nodding toward the demonstrators. `` If <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> were still in power, most of them would be cheering for him instead of <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>.''
