<HEAD>First Transvestites To Be Convicted Under New Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two men who dressed and behaved like women in public were both fined by the <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Religious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> under a law that took effect this year, a newspaper reported today. The Star said <PERSON> Ismail </PERSON> <PERSON> Awang </PERSON>, 31, and <PERSON> Amdan </PERSON> <PERSON> Osman </PERSON>, 42, were the first to be convicted under the law, which applies to Moslems in <LOCATION> Kedah </LOCATION> state. Under the law, a transvestite caught in a public place can be fined up to 1,000 ringgits -LRB- $ 366 -RRB- or jailed for six months. The two men each paid $ 183 fines in lieu of spending four months in jail. The two were caught in a raid by Religious Affairs Department officers on a street in Alor Star on Feb. 4, Prosecutor <PERSON> Ustaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mansor </PERSON> <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> told the court Sunday in <LOCATION> Alor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Star </LOCATION>, 210 miles north of the capital, the newspaper reported. The two were wearing skirts and T-shirts and were soliciting when arrested, the paper said.
