<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When your name is <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON>, you have to have a sense of humor. Just ask him. `` I remember once I needed a reservation at a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, hotel and I called and made it in my name,'' <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> said recently. `` But when I showed up, they had no reservation. They thought it had been a prank call. ... `` You ca n't take it seriously or your life would be miserable,'' said <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON>, who works for the <ORGANIZATION> Nebraska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> in 1931 during his namesake's presidential administration Given his name, it's only natural he once bought a pickup truck from a man named <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Harding </PERSON> -LRB- not the 29th president -RRB-, and that his office mate when he worked for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> was <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> -LRB- not the former <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-. He said most people have forgotten former president <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON>, but many kid him about the <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> vacuum cleaner. `` You have to get used to people laughing at you,'' he said. `` My name shocks people,'' <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> said, `` so I started saying <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> over the phone. But a few years ago, <ORGANIZATION> Burger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> had an advertising campaign featuring a guy named <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> and I started finding ` Where's <PERSON> Herb </PERSON>?' posters all over my office.'' Although he has n't changed his name, <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> has given his son a different start. `` My son's name is <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> said. `` I would never do that -LRB- name him <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> -RRB-. Children have enough to worry about.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> sweet potato growers have an identity crisis on their hands. Just last month, they finally got rid of the name `` yam'' from the name of their trade group to make a distinction between their product and the related African tuber. The state grows no yams, but its $ 60 million crop represents 40 percent of the nation's sweet potatoes. Now the federal government has decided sweet potato is really one word: sweetpotato. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> is apparently worried that consumers might think a sweet potato is an Irish potato that's sweet. `` That's the government bureaucracy for you,'' grumbled <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Horne </PERSON>, a salesman for <ORGANIZATION> Corbett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farms </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> wants the state's growers, and their trade group, to go along. The <ORGANIZATION> N.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sweetpotato </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has agreed, says <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeargin </PERSON>, executive director of the group. But the Sweet Potato Council of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, a Washington-based grower group, stands by its spelling. `` Just because the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> does it that way means <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> does also,'' said director <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoecker </PERSON>, noting with pride: `` But we at the council do not.'' <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commissioner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> does n't see what all the fuss is about. `` To heck with how you spell it,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said in an interview with The Charlotte Observer. `` We'll spell it any way they want as long as people are buying them.''
