<FIRST>r w PM-US-CentralAmerica     02-13 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Central America,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prospective Latin Aide Calls For Downgrading Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Democrat who is set to become <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's top aide for <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was once a strong supporter of the Nicaraguan Contras but now believes other strategies should be pursued for achieving a settlement in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON>, who once advised President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>, believes the new administration should make an all-out effort to build on the peace agreement the five Central American presidents signed in August 1987. <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON>'s views were outlined in a little-noticed paper he co-authored last October which was intended to influence the debate over <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> as the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration was bowing out. The report was published by <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a human rights group based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Eight others participated in writing the paper, titled `` Peace Through Democracy, A Bipartisan Initiative for the Central American Crisis.'' Although there have been some objections to <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON>'s prospective appointment, administration aides say Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> has indicated that his decision is final. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> has placed high priority on filling the post, vacated last month by <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>, with someone who will have more success than <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> did in forging a bipartisan policy on <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. While the policies of the new administration are still in the planning stage, the Central Americans themselves are engaged in a flurry of diplomatic activity. Central American foreign ministers met in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> last week and the five regional presidents were opening a two-day meeting today in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> to discuss the future of the Nicaraguan Contras and other issues. <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON>, 42, helped write a pro-Contra aid speech for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> several years ago but the report he helped write last fall suggests his views on rebel aid have shifted in light of new developments. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> has discussed the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> issue only in general terms but what he has said appears to be consistent with the substance of the report co-authored by <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON>. While hinting that <PERSON> Contra </PERSON> aid may be a last resort at some point, the report suggests that continued pursuit of that approach is tactically unwise because of hostile public opinion in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` Those who favor the immediate resumption of military aid to the <LOCATION> Nicaraguan </LOCATION> resistance are in danger of once again launching a military policy from a weak political base,'' the report said. It said few believe there is a broad enough consensus in support of <LOCATION> Contra </LOCATION> aid to sustain that approach for a substantial period. Instead, the report recommends giving a `` rigorous test'' to the <LOCATION> Esquipulas </LOCATION> agreement, signed by the five <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> presidents 18 months ago. Among other provisions, the agreement commits <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist government to establish democracy and also bars continued <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to the Contras. Six months after the agreement was signed, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> suspended military aid to the rebels, most of whom have since fled to camps along the Honduran border where they receive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> humanitarian assistance. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration was deeply mistrustful of the agreement, seeing it as a mechanism that would relieve Contra military pressure on the Sandinista government without ensuring a democratic outcome in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. American officials have repeatedly accused the Sandinista government of dragging its feet in adopting democratic reforms. <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> maintained that Contra military pressure was the only way to ensure a democratic evolution in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON> suggests that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration should have pursued more vigorously the opening created at <LOCATION> Esquipulas </LOCATION>, the site in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> where the agreement was signed. The <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> report said the accord has `` greater moral and political validity than other approaches being considered.'' On the other hand, it said the agreement has a number of weaknesses, including a lack of `` compelling verification and enforcement mechanisms'' and a reluctance `` to confront Soviet and <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> involvement in the region's turmoil.'' Among other recommendations, the report calls for the establishment of a bipartisan task force to determine whether the agreement is an appropriate instrument for bringing about peace and democracy in the region.
