<HEAD>Caucus Looks for Action After Bush's Reform Pledge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The image and words heartened members of the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reform </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION>. There was President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, standing on the deck of the 1,048-foot-long carrier <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> last month at the huge <ORGANIZATION> Norfolk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> and telling <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> personnel and contractor employees that he wants `` tighter controls and higher standards in weapons procurement.'' `` I'm very hopeful. I know the president intends to make changes,'' says Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, R-Del. `` We have a tremendous opportunity in the next few years,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON>, D-Calif. <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> and <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON> _ representatives of different sides of the aisle and different sides of the Capitol _ last week were named co-chairs of the caucus, an informal, bipartisan organization of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> members The Republican-Democratic, House-Senate mix is standard. During the 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the caucus membership totaled 136 with 27 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and 109 members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. Seventy-eight were Democrats and 58 were Republicans. Members are `` of a like mind concerned about reform in the military,'' said <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON>. At times during the eight-year tenure of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s predecessor, <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, the caucus was frustrated. For example, in 1983, it led the fight for the creation of an independent Pentagon operational test and evaluation office, but the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration delayed the installation of a test director until two years later. During the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presidency and the accompanying record peacetime military buildup, scandals surfaced about <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> payment of exorbitant prices for hammers, wrenches and toilet seats. Of a more serious nature, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has been pursuing a two-year probe of alleged purchasing fraud. The case involves charges that private consultants, hired by military contractors, bribed <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials to obtain inside information that gave companies an edge in bidding for <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> work. `` <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is the true father of the caucus,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Colo </LOCATION>., a member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and a frequent critic of the past Republican administration The caucus says its purpose is not to advocate `` overall increases or decreases in defense spending, only more effective expenditure of those dollars allocated for national defense.'' `` The notion is not to argue what weapons are needed. We're trying to find a way to make the most of the military for less money,'' said <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON> The caucus began in 1981 after former Rep. <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitehurst </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>., noticed an article in The Wall Street Journal on military reform The story's author was former <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> senator and onetime presidential candidate <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>. In reading the article, <PERSON> Whitehurst </PERSON> found that he shared some of the same views as <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>. The senator and the congressman huddled on military reform, joined forces with a handful of others and formed the caucus. Initially, the organization concentrated on such military reforms as maneuver tactics and leadership training. Later, as the caucus increased in numbers, it turned its attention to purchasing reform and conventional weapons. The organization says its activities `` are intended to support the regular committee work for a more effective national defense.'' `` We've held hearings we could n't get the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to hold. The caucus has pushed <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON> said. The caucus has no budget, no dues, not even an official phone number. Its staff is the staff of the co-chairs who handle mailings and pay for events. The caucus holds frequent briefings and seminars for members on such issues as the <ORGANIZATION> Bradley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fighting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vehicle </ORGANIZATION>, the military budget and conventional defense. This congressional session, the focus will be on promoting legislation to strengthen the procurement system and whistleblower protection, and tighten the revolving door between the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> and the defense industry, said <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>. Affecting the reform effort will be the budget crunch facing the Pentagon. In his speech Thursday, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed a $ 308.8 billion defense budget for fiscal 1990, eliminating the 2 percent increase proposed by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in January. `` With less funds available, it will be critically important that we get the biggest bang for the buck,'' said <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>. `` Centralized procurement within the department _ this kind of approach is the highest priority on the agenda.'' <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, who has been called a `` cheap hawk,'' jokes that he has to `` live up to his reputation.''
