<HEAD>Gambling Resort's Fortune Tellers May Be Subject To Criminal Checks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 People who predict the future will have to reveal their past if officials in this gambling resort get their way. City council last week unanimously passed a measure to require palm readers to undergo a criminal check, fingerprinting and positive identification when they go for their annual license. The city currently charges a $ 400 license fee for readers to practice their trade. `` The city ca n't deal in morality, but it can regulate things better,'' said <PERSON> Councilwoman </PERSON> <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmentieri </PERSON>, who proposed the measure. The council will take a final vote Wednesday. Many established readers support the effort. `` People come in here to work for a couple of months, and we do n't know who they really are,'' said <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, part of a palm-reading family that has operated here for more than 50 years. `` We want the tighter restrictions. It gives us the best protection.'' <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Annette </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Boardwalk </LOCATION> phrenologist _ someone who claims to detect character traits in the shape of a person's skull _ said the legalization of gambling 10 years ago has increased demand for fortune tellers' services and the need for tougher licensing regulations. `` We get a lot of bus people who want a reading to see how their luck is running,'' she said. `` Most of <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s readers have been here for a long time. But since the casinos came, a lot of new -LRB- readers -RRB- came in.'' <LOCATION> Altantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> required non-resident workers to register with the city from 1953 to 1972, but it was dropped after civil rights groups complained it violated individuals' rights, Police Chief <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Pasquale </PERSON> said. `` It was a good system, though, because we found people who were wanted for murder in other states,'' <PERSON> Pasquale </PERSON> said.
