<TEXT>
 A new comedy, `` Without Apologies,'' is full of the old-fashioned kind of laughs that come when belief is suspended and theater not overly concerned with realistic situations. `` Without Apologies'' is playing at the off-Broadway <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guild </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Theater </LOCATION>, where it had its <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> premiere Sunday. Irish actress <PERSON> Pauline </PERSON> <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON> shines in the role she also had at the play's debut at the <LOCATION> Dorset </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, Theater Festival. As <PERSON> Gwen </PERSON>, a plump, droll and sensible housewife in a genteelly shabby home, she dithers with delicious timing and inflections. The <PERSON> Thom </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> comedy is about the later years of the characters from `` The Importance of Being Earnest,'' the 1895 play that led to playwright <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilde </PERSON> being sued for having libeled the Beaumont family. In the 34 years since <PERSON> Ernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Beaumont </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Pagan </PERSON> -RRB- left <PERSON> Gwen </PERSON>, his bride-to-be -LRB- Miss <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON> -RRB-, at the altar and ran off with <PERSON> Cecily </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON> <PERSON> Nye </PERSON> -RRB-, the fiancee of his brother, <LOCATION> Algy </LOCATION> Beaumont -LRB- <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Knudson </PERSON> -RRB-, the two couples have had no contact. <PERSON> Gwen </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Algy </LOCATION>, the two left behind, married and live in her mother's house, with her mother and a renter upstairs. When <PERSON> Ernie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cecily </PERSON> arrive virtually unannounced for a visit, they bring their daughter <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Brutsman </PERSON> -RRB-, dressed like a child but 30. An unforgiving <PERSON> Gwen </PERSON> says it would be inconvenient for them to spend the night, but they inform her they're broke and moving in permanently. That sets up the plot: <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> get together with the renter -LRB- <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> -RRB-, a jazz drummer who aspires to be a comedian? <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Cecily </PERSON>, played by the blonde, willowy Miss <PERSON> Nye </PERSON>, forsake plummy-voice <PERSON> Ernie </PERSON> for <LOCATION> Algy </LOCATION> and scramble the family again? And there's one more question: Will the <LOCATION> Beaumont </LOCATION> descendants sue <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, director <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Lansbury </PERSON> and masterful set designer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wulp </PERSON>? With jokes about the footstool, a brotherly competition over war wounds and Miss <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON> crooning her comic lines up and down her vocal register, one is simply laughing too much to care.
