<HEAD>Dollar Highers, Stocks Fall in Tokyo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS 3 grafs to UPDATE with close. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``A
hike ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar was stronger against the Japanese yen Monday, while stock prices declined moderately in reaction to a hike in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prime lending rate. The dollar ended the day's trading at 128.30 yen, up 0.65 yen from Friday's close of 127.65 yen. It traded in a range of 128.20-128 .63 yen and was quoted at 128.50 yen at midday On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, a 53.56-point winner Friday, closed 146.67 points or 0.4 percent lower at 31,985.32. It finished last week at a record high 32,131.99 points. A hike in the prime lending rate from 10.5 percent to 11 percent by many American commercial banks and the news of a higher-than-expected <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producer price index for January, both announced Friday, combined to spur the dollar's rally, said a dealer at the Bank of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. The dollar dipped slightly in midmorning selling, but rebounded somewhat later. Trading was slow, the dealer said. The dollar's direction hinges on what happens to overseas interest rates, so players here are inclined, in the absence of any compelling incentives to trade during <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> business hours, to let the European and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets take the lead, the dealer added, speaking on condition of anonymity. The prime lending rate is closely watched because bankers use it as a basis for calculating interest on corporate loans and for determining various types of fixed and adjustable-rate consumer loans, including home equity loans. Higher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates make the dollar more attractive to foreign investors, but tend to have a negative impact on stock prices. <PERSON> Kazuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakamura </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Wako </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> share prices declined in reaction to the interest rate hike and also to the defeat of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Sunday in a closely watched parliamentary by-election. The election was seen as an indication of public sentiment toward the <ORGANIZATION> LDP </ORGANIZATION> following the passage of a long-sought tax reform package last December that included introduction of an unpopular 3 percent sales tax.
