<HEAD>Harris Took Winding Path to Historic Position As First Female Bishop</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Female Bishop, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With the shepherd's crook, robes and miter of an Episcopal bishop, the Rev. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> moves out into a flock divided over the question of whether she has the right to hold her newly acquired rank. To the duties of ordaining priests, granting communion and serving as a liaison among parishes in one of the nation's largest Episcopal dioceses, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Clementine </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> must add the burden of convincing many doubters within her church and other Christian denominations that she is suited to her new role. It is a challenge that <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, no stranger to controversy, says she is ready to take on. Following her consecration Saturday as suffragan, or assistant, bishop in the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> diocese, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> pledged to try to heal the divisions in the church created by her new rank. `` All of us, in the office of bishop, will be reaching out to as many people in the diocese and the whole church as we possibly can,'' said <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, her voice raspy from a cold. `` I feel good. I'm looking forward to getting on with my ministry. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, 58, became the first woman bishop in any branch of Christianity that traces its bishops directly to the time of Christ. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> has been involved in church activities throughout her life. But the first step toward her historic new position may have been taken in 1974, when <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> led a procession of `` the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> 11,'' a group of women Episcopalians who were ordained priests a full two years before the ordination of women was approved by the whole church. `` I was very much involved in the planning of that service,'' said <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, who was born and raised in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` It deeply affected me.'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>' career in private business and the church led her to prisons, corporate board rooms, divorce court and the editorial desk of a feisty, liberal publication. Because that path did not include a college or seminary degree and because of what some view as her extreme left-wing views _ to say nothing of her gender _ <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>' consecration touched off heated debate. The issue of a woman becoming a bishop would have engendered debate throughout <LOCATION> Christendom </LOCATION> regardless who was nominated. But <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> provoked all the more discussion because of her background. Some of the opposition to her elevation stemmed from her race as well as her sex, said <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, who is black. During the 1960s <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> became involved in the civil rights movement and participated in the <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, march led by the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. For a decade beginning in 1958, she worked in a public relations firm and, beginning in 1968, for <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s public relations department, ending her career there in 1980 as a senior staff That year <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> assumed the robes of an Episcopal priest and began a career that took her to counseling sessions in prisons and sermons in a city parish. In 1984, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> became executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, an organization not officially sanctioned by the church but one with a considerable voice through its publication, The Witness. It was in the pages of this monthly magazine that <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> became known to a wider audience through her regular editorials. She wrote editorials against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s apartheid policies and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to rebels in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. She wrote in favor of homosexual rights and an end to church discrimination against homosexuals. She also lambasted conservative wings of the church on many occasions, sometimes angering as much with her style as with the substance of her commentary. In 1963, after three years of marriage, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> divorced <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Rollins </PERSON>, which also was cited by some critics. She likes classical music and drinks an occasional glass of chablis. She prefers `` any kind of gourmet food,'' but also likes soul food, especially black-eyed peas. `` I like cooking up a storm for a large crowd,'' she said.
