<HEAD>Church Traces History To Roots of Christianity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Female Bishop, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> has taken her place as the first woman bishop in church that traces its heritage directly to early days of Christianity, despite a stormy break with Catholicism during the reign of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> VIII </PERSON>. The 2.8 million-member <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> developed from the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> and is one of the several independent national churches that belong to the worldwide Anglican Communion. English settlers brought the church to <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> at the turn of the 17th century. It became a separate group when it adopted a constitution and religious laws and a revision of the Book of Common Prayer in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> in 1789. The Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> had separated from the Roman Catholic church in the 16th century after <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> VIII </PERSON> was denied an annulment to his marriage to <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> of </PERSON> <PERSON> Aragon </PERSON>, who had no sons. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> secretly married his second of six wives, <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Boleyn </PERSON>, rejected the pope's authority in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and appointed <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranmer </PERSON> <PERSON> Archbishop </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Canterbury </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cranmer </PERSON> approved <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>'s annulment. In 1534, <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> declared that the pope had no authority in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and made the Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> a separate institution. The communion contends that its clergy are directly linked to the apostles of Christ through an unbroken series of ceremonies. Other denominations claims the same kind of historic succession, including the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> voted in 1976 to allow women priests. Since then about 1,200 have been ordained. The church is governed by a permanent Executive Council and by the General Convention, which meets every three years.
