<TEXT>
 Cupid has been working overtime in this southwestern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> town as Valentine's Day nears. Up to 14,000 requests in a year have been sent for a special red postmark showing the angel of love, the town's name and the slogan `` There is nothing in this world so sweet as love,'' said <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> As </ORGANIZATION> its renown for the love-struck grows, more residents of the community of 10,000 people are getting into the act as volunteer postmark stampers. `` It's involving a lot more people than it has in the past. This year, we opened it up to the community,'' <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said last week. `` Each piece of mail is handled individually.'' Although the postmark is available year-round, the mail requesting it peaks as Feb. 14 approaches. Volunteers stamp the special postmark by hand on each letter. The <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> post office helps publicize the project and asks people to send their prepaid and pre-addressed mail to <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> in a larger envelope. <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> resident <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> <PERSON> Pfiester </PERSON> began the project in 1971 and faithfully pursued it until her 1982 death. Her daughter, <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, took it over and kept it up. This year, with all the added volunteer help, she was able to take a vacation.
