<HEAD>Dollar Rebounds, Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rebounded against the Japanese yen today, while stock prices declined on profit-taking selling following six consecutive days of record-high closings. Both markets reacted early in the day to a rise Friday in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prime lending rate, which pushed the dollar higher but depressed stock prices. The stock market also reacted negatively to local political developments. The dollar, which fell 1.74 yen last Friday to a closing of 127.65 yen, gained back 0.65 yen on Monday, closing at 128.30 yen. After opening at 128.50 yen, the dollar weakened on mid-morning selling, recovered and later sagged as several banks sold the currency to protect their bond holdings, said <PERSON> Kaneo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ogino </PERSON>, a trader at <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION>. It traded in a range of 128.20-128 .63 yen An increase in the prime lending rate from 10.5 percent to 11 percent by many American commercial banks and news of an unexpectedly high <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producer price index for January, both announced Friday, combined to spur the dollar's early rally, said a dealer at the Bank of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` Now everyone's paying attention to interest-rate differentials and inflation, which should be good for the dollar,'' <PERSON> Ogino </PERSON> said. Higher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates tend to make the dollar more attractive to foreign investors. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, a 53.56-point gainer Friday, closed 146.67 points, or 0.4 percent, lower at 31,985.32. It finished last week at a record high 32,131.99 points. Share prices declined in reaction to the interest rate hike and to the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s loss Sunday in a closely watched parliamentary by-election, said <PERSON> Kazuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakamura </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Wako </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. `` After the <ORGANIZATION> LDP </ORGANIZATION>'s severe defeat and six straight days of -LRB- stock index -RRB- increase, investors felt it was time to ease off,'' <PERSON> Nakamura </PERSON> said. The election to fill the seat of a Liberal Democrat who died in December was the first race for a national office since the so-called Recruit stock scandal over financial links between <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and prominent politicians and bureaucrats came to light. The election also was seen as an indication of public opinion toward the governing party following the passage of a long-sought tax reform package in December that included introduction of an unpopular 3 percent sales tax.
