<HEAD>First Black Families In South Boston Housing Projects Happy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Separate Cities, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the first two black families moved into the virtually all-white housing projects of south <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> last summer, they were accompanied by police. After weeks of protests by neighbors and extensive news coverage, city officials feared a replay of the 1970s riots over the busing of blacks to schools in the working class section. Instead, more than six months later, the two families report little enmity and much hospitality. `` I'm just a neighbor like anyone else,'' said <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Clinkscales </PERSON>, 37, who lives in a three-bedroom apartment with her 20-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Anjanette </PERSON>, and grandson, <PERSON> Jahman </PERSON>, 4. `` I have n't experienced much animosity since I've been here. I think south <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s in a healing process now.'' The move for <PERSON> Clinkscales </PERSON> and the family of <PERSON> Bessie </PERSON> <PERSON> Payne </PERSON>, 36, was made easier because the two have been friends since high school. Coincidentally, they were both given eviction notices about the same time and applied for emergency housing with the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>. `` My main focus at that time was not to become homeless, not to go into a shelter,'' said <PERSON> Clinkscales </PERSON>, who works as an assistant at a day-care center and pays $ 225 a month for her apartment. `` To me that was just as frightening as moving to south <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Payne </PERSON> tells a similar story. `` I could n't see myself in a shelter with the children and I saw no reason to be when <ORGANIZATION> BHA </ORGANIZATION> had a three-bedroom apartment available,'' <PERSON> Payne </PERSON> said. Until recently, the projects in the predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> neighborhood known as <LOCATION> Southie </LOCATION> were 98 percent white and 2 percent non-black minorities. But since the <PERSON> Clinkscales </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Paynes </ORGANIZATION> moved into <LOCATION> Southie </LOCATION>, several other black families have been placed in the projects. It was in the same neighborhood, separated from downtown by a harbor channel, where years of protests erupted after court-ordered busing in 1974. Whites stoned buses of black children shuttled from the <LOCATION> Roxbury </LOCATION> section. After federal authorities told <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> officials to desegregate the projects last year, Mayor <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> held meetings in south <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> to urge acceptance of the plan. Instead, they booed <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, a south <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> native, and called him a traitor. When <PERSON> Clinkscales </PERSON> and <PERSON> Payne </PERSON> moved in last July, the city had developed a long-term `` safety plan'' for them in case of trouble. For the first week, the two families were told to check in with police when they left their apartments and when they returned. `` My image was that there was some prejudice here but I'm the type of person who realizes there's prejudice everywhere,'' said <PERSON> Clinkscales </PERSON>. <PERSON> Clinkscales </PERSON> and <PERSON> Payne </PERSON> said in recent interviews that little has happened to make them feel like the targets of bigotry. `` When I moved in, I expected a lot of turbulence,'' said <PERSON> Payne </PERSON>, 37, who is an administrator at a church, and shares her apartment with her son, <PERSON> Kimani </PERSON> <PERSON> Poles </PERSON>, 14, and daughter, <PERSON> Dadizi </PERSON> <PERSON> Poles </PERSON>, 9. `` When it did n't happen, I was really grateful. I think the people here are willing to accept change now.'' The two said they give each other moral support with daily phone calls. Yet the only disturbing incident for both came when teen-agers once yelled racial slurs outside their apartments. They said it occurred just once. <PERSON> Clinkscales </PERSON>' daughter, <PERSON> Anjanette </PERSON>, said she and her mother exchanged Christmas gifts with the <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> family next door and counts 18-year-old <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> as a friend. `` I was surprised at how nice they were,'' said <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>, who said she had never known a black family until the <PERSON> Clinkscales </PERSON> moved in.
