<PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> rocket team during World War II and a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> was in charge of production of the V-2 missile in the underground <LOCATION> Mittelwerk </LOCATION> factory about 140 miles south of <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION>. The area is now part of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said thousands of concentration camp prisoners were worked to death or executed at <LOCATION> Mittelwerk </LOCATION>. It charged that <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> influenced what happened there. <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON>, who was living in retirement in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> when the charges were made, said he `` never pleaded guilty but they talk anyway about alleged things that I did, not proven, and I'm not guilty.'' <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Haeussermann </PERSON>, who worked with <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> in <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and again in development of <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> rockets at <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>, said the campaign for restoration of <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizenship would continue, but that efforts would focus now on his request for a temporary visa. `` We think the fight for -LRB- <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON>'s -RRB- exoneration may take longer and we would like to get permission for him to visit here even temporarily to be part of the reunion _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> owes him that,'' <PERSON> Haeussermann </PERSON> said. In exchange for <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON>'s agreement to leave rather than fight the accusations, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> agreed not to challenge the American citizenship of his