<SECOND>PM-Pedophile Privacy,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maryland Legislature Rethinking Confidentiality Privileges For Pedophiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislators are having second thoughts about a unique law that grants confidentiality to pedophiles who confess to psychiatrists. Although the legislature removed some privileges last year, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> remains the only state that grants patient-doctor privilege if the pedophile discloses sexual abuse of children, or even simple child abuse, that occurred before seeking treatment from a psychiatrist who specializes in treating pedophilia. Dr. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlin </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sexual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disorders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinic </ORGANIZATION>, said in a recent interview that if he were required by law to report a pedophile's past, that person probably would n't come forward for treatment. He and others in his specialty won special confidentiality privileges from the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 to encourage pedophiles to get help. Now, the lawmakers want to force psychiatrists to report instances of past abuse that a pedophile reveals at any time _ even at his initial psychiatric evaluation. Child advocates and social services officials backing the bill maintain it's more important to protect a child's rights than to guarantee any privacy to the offender. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Comstock-Gay </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>'s executive director, said the bill presents `` an interesting privacy issue.'' The state <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> has yet to take a final position on the proposed change, which passed the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last month. The House has yet to schedule debate on the bill. `` There's always a balance between individual rights and another interest in the public safety and public health,'' <PERSON> Comstock-Gay </PERSON> said. `` I'm sure on the surface, it must seem it's good for children to report -LRB- the abuse -RRB-, and bad not to,'' said <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, who believes more abuse may be uncovered by encouraging pedophiles to enter treatment. Noting that clergymen who counsel pedophiles and lawyers who refer them to psychiatrists for treatment are not compelled by law to report them, he added: `` My concern is that people who otherwise might have come forward would be deterred from doing so.'' For example, without the assurance of confidentiality, one of his patients, an attorney involved sexually with his daughter, never would have sought help, nor would therapists necessarily have gotten his daughter into counseling, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> said. `` There's no way he wanted to risk being disbarred. He very much wanted treatment,'' <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> said. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advocacy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, believes some abuse could remain hidden by such privileged communications `` It concerns me that the balance with that sort of law tips toward protection of the offender,'' said <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>. `` What about the rights of all of his victims?'' State Sen. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, who introduced the bill to strip the reporting exemption, subscribes to the once-a-pedophile, always-a-pedophile school of thought. `` Everybody admits they -LRB- pedophiles -RRB- ca n't be cured,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` I am of the opinion that they ca n't even be treated. I'd rather see them in jail, that's where they belong. However, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> believes his program of intensive psychotherapy, in tandem sometimes with hormone treatments, can curb pedophilia. He also said that when a patient appears to be a danger to others, he wo n't hesitate to commit him to a hospital ward for sex offenders. `` It's so easy to be in the corner where you seem to be against kids, or victims. When things get pigeon-holed, it puts pressure on legislators, and it certainly makes it uncomfortable for me,'' <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> said. `` I do n't think there's a cure, but I do believe people, with help, can control themselves appropriately. It's like alcoholism; today we have the <ORGANIZATION> Betty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinic </ORGANIZATION>.''
