<HEAD>Jewish Cultural Center Opens in Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet Jews celebrated a measure of religious freedom with the opening of the first Jewish community center in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 50 years. Soviet Jews and Jewish leaders from 70 nations filled the building in downtown <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Sunday for the opening. <PERSON> Elie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiesel </PERSON>, an author and winner of the 1986 Nobel Peace Prize, said the reforms of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> made the center possible. `` Today is a time to say ` thank you,''' <PERSON> Wiesel </PERSON> said. `` I think he deserves our trust.'' The opening of the <ORGANIZATION> Solomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mikhoels </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, named after a Soviet Jewish actor who died in the Stalinist oppression in 1948, represents a significant change in relations between the government and the country's 1.8 million Jews. It came just a few days after a Soviet newspaper made a major admission: that Soviet Jews have suffered discrimination for decades and that dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> destroyed Jewish culture in the country. The center is in the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Jewish Musical Theater on <LOCATION> Taganka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> in the southeastern section of the capital. For Jews, greater tolerance by the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> has meant a rise in emigration _ including an eight-year high of 20,000 in 1988 _ less harassment at Jewish holiday celebrations and the opening of a private Jewish museum and library in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. World Jewish Congress President <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronfman </PERSON> also praised <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, saying his reforms made it possible to `` hope for a great revival of Jewish culture and religion in the U.S.S.R.'' But he added it will be some years before Soviet Jews overcome their fear of religious repression in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where the teaching of Hebrew was once outlawed. He also expressed worry that the cultural center could become the target of anti-Semitism. <PERSON> Wiesel </PERSON> said he still hopes `` to see in history books a recognition that the main victims of <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> were Jewish _ because they were Jewish, not because they were Communists and Russian citizens.'' Sunday's ceremony drew Jewish leaders from around the world, including former Soviet refusenik <PERSON> Yuli </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelstein </PERSON>, now an executive of the Soviet Jewry Zionist Forum in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> vice president <PERSON> Isi </PERSON> <PERSON> Leibler </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>; and Rabbi <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hier </PERSON>, dean of the <ORGANIZATION> Simon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wiesenthal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The cultural center is particularly important because decades of repression have left most of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s Jews with virtually no knowledge of their religion, history and culture. `` Soviet Jews are not really Jews,'' said <PERSON> Edelstein </PERSON>, who served three years in prison for teaching Hebrew. The cultural center opened with a photo exhibit on the Holocaust. Organizers hope to offer classes in Yiddish and Hebrew, films, exhibits, music and a cafe featuring Jewish food, said director <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gluz </PERSON>. The ambassadors of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOC