<HEAD>Blast Kills Arab; Troops Critically Wound Two Teen-agers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with explosion killing Arab; teen-agers
critically wounded. Picks up 4th graf pvs, ``We are ...'' EDITS thereafter
to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An explosion killed a Palestinian in the occupied territories today, and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops critically wounded two Arab teen-agers during a stone-throwing riot, the army said. In <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, two left-wing members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> said recent attacks by Israelis on Palestinians in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> are the work of a `` very efficient and well armed'' Jewish settler militia. The army imposed a curfew on <LOCATION> Kabatiya </LOCATION> village in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> after an unidentified man accidentally blew himself up in an blast that hurt two other villagers, a military spokesman said. `` A preliminary report indicates they found a suspicious object, played with it and it exploded,'' said a military statement. An Arab reporter in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> said a 4-year-old girl and her 10-year-old brother were seriously hurt while herding sheep near their Tayasir village home. The children's parents said they heard an explosion, but do not know its cause. It was not immediately clear whether the army and the <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> reporter described the same incident. Tayasir and <LOCATION> Kabatiya </LOCATION> are 10 miles apart. A military spokesman denied the man was killed inside <LOCATION> Kabatiya </LOCATION>, but refused to elaborate. At least six other children have been reported wounded in similar mysterious blasts, which the government is investigating. <PERSON> Ehud </PERSON> <PERSON> Barak </PERSON>, deputy chief of staff of the armed forces, has said some injuries were caused by flares emitted by fighter jets to deflect heat-seeking missiles. A few flares fall to earth instead of exploding, he said. In the occupied <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Rafah </LOCATION> refugee camp today, two 14-year-olds were shot in the head by troops. They were in critical condition in Israeli hospitals, a military spokeswoman said. Two <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> legislators from the left-wing <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> sent a letter to Attorney General <PERSON> Yosef </PERSON> <PERSON> Harish </PERSON> charging there is a well-organized militia of several hundred settlers armed with automatic weapons, vehicles and advanced communications sytems. Settler leaders denied an organized militia exists. The lawmakers' letter was sent Sunday after 40 settlers stormed into a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> mayor's office to protest stonings and firebombings of settlers' cars. The army spirited Mayor <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sneineh </PERSON> out of his <LOCATION> Qalqilya </LOCATION> office and forced the settlers to leave. `` We are calling on the attorney general to break up this militia,'' said <PERSON> Yossi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarid </PERSON>, who authored the letter with <PERSON> Dedi </PERSON> <PERSON> Zucker </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sarid </PERSON> said bands of settler vigilante groups started forming a few months ago in response to <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> attacks on some of the 70,000 Jewish settlers who uneasily share the occupied lands with 1.7 million Arabs. Settlers formed the militia because they have lost faith in the army's ability to protect them, <PERSON> Sarid </PERSON> said. Settler leader <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Nachman </PERSON>, named in the letter as a key militia chief, said the paramilitary organization was <PERSON> Sarid </PERSON>'s `` fantasy.'' `` There is a difference between a militia and people getting fed up and doing something,'' said <PERSON> Nachman </PERSON>, mayor of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> settlement of Ariel. However, he added that if the government does not take harsher measures to end the 14-month Palestinian uprising, such as deporting <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> leaders, more settler violence is likely. The settlers were protesting the death Wednesday of a 37-year-old Jewish taxi driver from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> settlement of <PERSON> Alfe </PERSON> <PERSON> Menashe </PERSON>. Police said <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Jerassi </PERSON> apparently was attacked by <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON>, but they have not discovered what caused his car to burst into flames as he drove past <LOCATION> Qalqilya </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jerassi </PERSON>'s death would raise to 16 the number of Israelis who have died in the Palestinian uprising. At least 380 Palestinians have been killed in the revolt against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s occupation of lands seized in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war.
