<HEAD>Presidents Meet to Discuss Central American Peace Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede SAN SALVADOR</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with summit opening. Picks up 6th
pvs, ``Among the ...'' Changes byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TESORO BEACH, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> opened a much-postponed Central American summit today, saying the five leaders are optimistic about bringing peace and progress to the turbulent region. Flanked by Presidents <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Vinicio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cerezo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> made the brief statement opening the meeting at <LOCATION> Tesoro </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, a seaside resort 40 miles southeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. `` I am sure that we, with optimism, will analyze the efforts we've made according to the <ORGANIZATION> Esquipulas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> II </ORGANIZATION> plan and search for favorable solutions that will promote peace and progress in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> said. Then the presidents went into closed session. The stalled peace plan was named for the Guatemalan city where the five presidents decided to sign the August 1987 agreement. Diplomats say <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s four neighbors plan to press its government for democratic reforms promised under the peace plan. `` The main roadblock in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> has been removed _ the Contras,'' said one diplomat referring to the decline of the Nicaraguan rebels called Contras. `` There are no more obstacles -LRB- to reform -RRB- and no more excuses.'' At the same time, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> probably has most to gain from the conference, which it hopes will help destroy the Contras. `` Among the most important things that will be dealt with at the summit is the matter of verification and control of borders,'' <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> told a news conference last week. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said upon his arrival Sunday that he believed the leaders `` are going to ratify'' a new plan to step up border controls to prevent the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> neighbors from supporting subversion against one another. Central American foreign ministers met <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> last week and called for creation of `` an impartial mechanism'' to verify compliance along borders. About 11,000 Contras remain in Honduran camps near <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s border, but the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has made no request for renewed military aid and senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials acknowledge the era of an anti-Sandinista army as an arm of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy has passed <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> has scheduled elections for 1990 and has met with opposition leaders to discuss its recent economic austerity measures, but the opposition claims Sandinista talk of democratic reform is window dressing. A Costa Rican diplomat said that unless the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> make `` precise commitments and agree to deadlines for democratization measures ... we will have to prepare for the peace plan's funeral and the Nicaraguans will have to accept responsibility for its demise.'' <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> won the Nobel Peace Prize for writing the plan, which is designed to bring peace and promote democracy in the turbulent region. `` We go to the summit full of optimism, despite the obstacles, because reality demands the search for solutions to the problems we Central Americans have,'' <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> was quoted as saying by the Costa Rican newspaper <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diario </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> la </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republica </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday. A summit in August was to mark the anniversary of the plan's signing, but the presidents, who last met 13 months ago, could not agree on an agenda The meeting has since been scheduled and postponed five times. When the peace plan was signed, stubborn civil wars plagued <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and the Contras were waging a fierce campaign against the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>'s U.S.-backed government and the leftist guerrillas battling it were unable to negotiate a cease-fire. <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>'s leftist rebels have been reduced to isolated zones but remain active, and <ORGANIZATION> Cerezo </ORGANIZATION>'s government has not sought negotiations The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> cut off military aid to the Contras a year ago, and the rebels signed a preliminary cease-fire with the Sandinistas in March. Although some fighting continues, it now is scattered and sporadic. <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, however, has been strongly criticized for failing to live up to the plan's requirement to strengthen democratic institutions and practices. Besides that, the plan calls for amnesties for political prisoners, a halt to outside aid to insurgents, and prohibits signatories from allowing their territory to be used as bases for attacks against another's territory.
