<HEAD>Soviet Delegate Says Kremlin Preparing New Human Rights Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> said Monday it is readying a series of laws in the human rights field, including freedom of the press and the right to leave the country. `` We are trying to implement fully our legislation in accordance with international standards,'' said <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanevski </PERSON>, the Soviet chief delegate to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are well aware that only by guaranteeing human rights and freedoms can we open up the whole potential of our society,'' he said in a speech in the 40-nation commission. Only by such guarantees, he said, can the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> `` improve the standards of living and quality of life of the people, solve the tasks of the environment and move science and technology forward.'' He said measures already adopted over a short period of time `` shall improve the situation of the people in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in a broad range of areas.'' Among the measures he mentioned were new provisions `` ensuring the right of the mentally ill'' and the `` opening of new monasteries and churches.'' `` Soon there will be another series of laws,'' he said. `` These have to do with the areas of freedom of conscience, of information and the press, -LRB- of -RRB- social organizations, and -LRB- of -RRB- entry and exit into and from the country.'' Reform of the Soviet criminal code also is being prepared, he said. `` Additional guarantees which will exclude the possibility of prosecution for political and religious convictions are also under way.'' In a brief interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Stanevski </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> `` probably'' woul