<SECOND>AM-Sleeping Aids,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Final Regulations Issued by FDA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> on Monday issued final regulations for non-prescription sleep-aid products that allow use of most of their active ingredients but bans other ingredients not proved safe and effective. The major sleep-aid products already meet the new standard and few changes will have to be made in product labeling, <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> officials said. The regulations are not much different from the agency's tentative recommendations on sleeping-aid ingredients issued in June 1978, said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Benson </PERSON>, a reviewing pharmacist with the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s division of over-the-counter drug The regulations, to be published in Tuesday's Federal Register, will take effect in one year. They were developed as part of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s review of all non-prescription drugs, which began in 1972. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> standard allows use of diphenhydramine hydrochloride and diphenhydramine citrate, contained in the sleep-aid products Compoz, <LOCATION> Nervine </LOCATION>, Nytol, Sleep-eze-3, Sleepinal, Sominex and Sominex-2, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. The agency also said approval of doxylamine succinate will remain in effect. That ingredient is in <LOCATION> Unisom </LOCATION>, Doxysom and Ultra Sleep. Not permitted are pyrilamine maleate, potassium bromide, sodium bromide and scopolamine hydrobromide. Products containing these ingredients must be reformulated, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>, in its tentative finding 10 years ago, had recommended banning these four ingredients unless they could be proved safe and effective, and as a result many sleeping-aid manufacturers stopped using them, <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> said. Claims on sleeping-aid product labels, substantially the same as those in the tentative recommendations, may include: helps you fall asleep if you have difficulty falling asleep; for relief of occasional sleeplessness; and helps to reduce difficulty falling asleep. Warning labels will have to be changed to add to the list of medical conditions that if present indicate the product should not be used. The new labels must warn against taking the product if you have asthma glaucoma, emphysema, chronic pulmonary disease, shortness of breath, difficulty in breathing or difficulty in urination due to enlargement of the prostate gland, unless directed by a doctor. The new labels also strengthen the caution involving alcohol, advising people to avoid alcoholic beverages while taking the product. It also advises against taking the product if also taking sedatives or tranquilizers, without consulting a doctor first.
</TEXT>
