<HEAD>Sweets ... And Some Not So Sweet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Big gifts and guilt sometimes go hand in hand, warns a psychologist taking aim at Cupids bearing surprisingly large or expensive Valentine's Day gifts. When someone is either falling out of love or already has done so, and is feeling guilty, `` sometimes they not only give a gift _ they go overboard,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>, a professor of psychology at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION>. A $ 2.50 card from someone who customarily sends a more modest greeting can be a tip-off. `` Superficially, gifts are always nice. But gifts can be given for the wrong reason _ flattery, ingratiation, wanting to get something from you, or guilt,'' <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> said. So how can one tell if a nice gift on Valentine's Day is a sign cupid is on the mark or off target? `` If this person has not done this in the past, and comes up with a big gift, that's something that needs to be thought about,'' he said. `` It could be either a sign of falling in love again or of feeling guilty.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
