<HEAD>FTC Says Company Will Donate Money to Medical Associations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that a <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> company will donate $ 600,000 to three medical associations to settle complaints of false advertising. The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> signed a consent decree under which it pledged not to make false or unsubstantiated claims about its products. Signing the decree is not an admission of any violations. Violation of its terms can mean a fine of $ 10,000. The commission said the company made false and unsubstantiated claims that its `` Healthy Greens'' diet supplement was effective in reducing the risk of cancer. Also, the commission said, the company falsely claimed that six other supplements, mainly sold to body builders, promoted weight loss, increased muscle growth and slowed aging. The consent order was approved by a 3-1 vote. Commissioner <PERSON> Margot </PERSON> <PERSON> Machol </PERSON> did not participate. The dissenter, Commissioner <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcuenaga </PERSON>, said the order left the company `` free to sell products it knows are deceptively labeled.'' The money will be split among the American <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diabetes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, a lawyer handling the case in the commission's <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> office, said such required donations were rare but had been used in the past Such a remedy was chosen, he said, because, `` it would be extrao