<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The second-ranking official of the <ORGANIZATION> Laborers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, identified by a presidential commission as having close ties to organized crime, retired Monday and was replaced by his son. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Coia </PERSON>, the union's secretary treasurer, announced his retirement at the union's annual Executive Council session in <LOCATION> Bal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbour </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Coia </PERSON>, regional manager for the Laborers in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and eastern <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, was immediately tapped to succeed his father Both men were mentioned in the 1986 report of the President's <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Organized Crime, which said the union had `` clear ties to organized crime. The elder <PERSON> Coia </PERSON>, 75, once was indicted on racketeering charges for allegedly accepting payoffs in return for steering union insurance business to selected companies. But the case was dismissed because the charges were filed after the statute of limitations had expired. The report, citing congressional investigations of organized crime influence on organized labor, also accused <PERSON> Coia </PERSON> and his son of involvement in schemes to bilk union health and welfare funds. The younger <PERSON> Coia </PERSON>, in a telephone interview, said both he and his father were `` unfairly characterized'' in the report and had no dealings with the mob. `` The mention of me and my father in that presidential commission report is really not a detailed and fair representation,'' he said. `` The so-called link to organized crime does not exist.'' The report also criticized internal union election policies, including the provision that allowed the younger <PERSON> Coia </PERSON>, 45, to be tapped to succeed his father. The Laborers union holds its convention every five years, when delegates elect candidates to the Executive Council on an at-large basis. If board vacancies occur between conventions, the remaining board members choose a replacement, a policy the report said `` leaves few offices contested.'' `` When the use of violence and intimidation are added, the membership has little opportunity to express itself dramatically,'' the presidential report said. The hearings on which the report was based included testimony that the elder <PERSON> Coia </PERSON> also sought to convince <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, a longtime vice president of the union and one of its few black leaders, not to run for union president. <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> testified that <PERSON> Coia </PERSON> told him the `` Italians'' had organized the union and would always control it. The report accused the elder <PERSON> Coia </PERSON> and Laborers President <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Fosco </PERSON> of abusive spending of union funds, including $ 200,000 authorized by <PERSON> Coia </PERSON> to pay for a private investigator to keep tabs on a longstanding federal investigation of the union. <PERSON> Coia </PERSON> also ordered the union to pay $ 40,000 requested by his son to cover legal fees stemming from a government investigation of the union, the report said. There has been speculation that Focso might step down from the union presidency this year, but the younger <PERSON> Coia </PERSON> discounted such talk. `` I think the rumors are all false,'' he said. The Coias both are <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> natives. The younger <PERSON> Coia </PERSON>, a labor attorney by trade, has a law practice in <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION>, R.I.
