<HEAD>Guerrillas Resume `Shura' Council Despite Factionalistm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Afghan guerrillas briefly resumed a council on Monday and tried to choose a Moslem government, but two important leaders did not attend and rival factions continued wrangling over shares of power. Guerrilla sources said the seven groups in the Pakistan-based guerrilla alliance were divided on who should lead an interim government in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and on apportioning the top positions. Differences also arose over including insurgent groups based in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, they said. <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> is predominantly Sunni Moslem, as are most guerrillas based in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Most of the insurgents in an eight-faction coalition that operates from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> are <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> Moslem, the sect of their host country. Some spokesmen said the council, known as a shura, would resume Tuesday and would consider major issues for the first time. Others said there was little or no hope of progress. `` The whole situation is such that nothing can come out of the council,'' said a senior official, who like the others spoke on condition of anonymity. Factionalism developed immediately Friday at the inaugural session of the shura, which has been seen as the last chance for feuding guerrilla groups to compromise, and it was suspended. Insurgent leaders predict the Marxist government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> will collapse soon after the last Soviet soldiers withdraw on Wednesday. The council's job is to choose a government that would take over and arrange elections. Aides said <PERSON> Sibghatullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mojaddidi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Syed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Gailani </PERSON>, who lead two of the seven parties, did not attend the Monday meeting and leaders of the five other other parties presided over the council, which did not consider major issues. <PERSON> Mojaddidi </PERSON> did not attend because the other six parties rejected his proposal for bringing the Iranian-based guerrillas in, sources reported. A spokesman for <PERSON> Mojaddidi </PERSON> said: `` The shura is not going to work out without the Iranian-based mujahedeen,'' using the word for the guerrillas that means Islamic holy warriors. <PERSON> Gailani </PERSON> aides said he had a scheduling conflict Monday but would attend the meeting Tuesday. But guerrilla sources said that he stayed away because of an argument about who would lead the interim government. Guerrilla groups summoned the council of insurgents, Moslem scholars and officials of past Afghan governments. <PERSON> Mojaddidi </PERSON>, who now holds the rotating chairmanship of the Pakistan-based alliance, has insisted the others honor his plan to give the <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> groups in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> 100 of the more than 500 council seats and seven interim government Cabinet posts. Most Sunni guerrilla leaders say the Shiites, an estimated 15 percent of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s population, are too few to receive so many seats. About 80 percent of Afghans are Sunni. <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> representatives have said they will accept only the <PERSON> Mojaddidi </PERSON> plan, but have not carried out their threat to leave <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>. Moslem guerrillas began fighting in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> after a Communist coup in April 1968 and Soviet soldiers entered the country in December 1979, reaching an estimated total of 115,000 by May 15, 1988, when the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> began withdrawing under a U.N.-mediated agreement. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and other countries have helped arm and finance the guerrillas.
