<HEAD>World Court Opens Hearing In U.S.-Italian Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hearings opened Monday at the World Court in a dispute between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> over the 1968 seizure of a U.S.-owned company, a court spokesman said. It is the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> case to be heard since the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration rejected a 1986 <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling ordering it to stop arming the Nicaraguan rebels known as Contras. Boston-based <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, an electronics company and defense contractor, estimates it lost $ 6 million plus interest in the takeover of its subsidiary company <ORGANIZATION> Elettronica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sicula </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.p.A. </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Sofaer </PERSON>, the legal advisor to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon </ORGANIZATION> wanted to liquidate the <LOCATION> Palermo </LOCATION>, Sicily-based manufacturer of cathode ray and vacuum tubes, but the Italian government nationalized the company to save jobs on the island plagued by unemployment. A five-judge panel is hearing the case, which is expected to continue at least until Wednesday, the court spokesman said on condition of anonymity. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration filed the suit two years ago for <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon </ORGANIZATION>, but only written arguments had been made since then. Only governments can appear before the court. Formally known as the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>, the judicial branch of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has no enforcement powers and depends on voluntary adherence to its rulings. <PERSON> Elettronica </PERSON> <PERSON> Sicula </PERSON>, also known as ELSI, was co-owned by <ORGANIZATION> Matchlett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company not involved in the case. The Italian government said expropriation of the company in 1968 was aimed at protecting the plant's 900 jobs after <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Matchlett </PERSON> disclosed their intention to shut down the concern. The judicial panel consists of the court's president, Judge <PERSON> Jose-Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruda </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, and Judges <PERSON> Shigeru </PERSON> <PERSON> Oda </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ago </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwebel </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and Sir <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The case was filed in February 1987 after the <ORGANIZATION> Reagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> rejected as invalid a <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling in July 1986 ordering the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to stop arming rebel forces attempting to overthrow <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist government. In apparent anticipation of that adverse ruling, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had withdrawn in March 1984 its recognition of the unlimited jurisdiction of the court, but said it would continue to accept the court's authority in cases not connected with the Central American issue. The <ORGANIZATION> ELSI </ORGANIZATION> case is the third one filed at the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in a decade. In 1979, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> asked the court to order the release by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> of 52 American diplomats held hostage in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. The court, on an emergency basis, ruled weeks later that the hostages should be released. They were ultimately freed in 1981. In the same year, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> jointly asked the court to draw the boundary between the two nations in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> off <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. That dispute was decided in 1984.
