<HEAD>Sihanouk Says Cambodian Peace Talks Will Fail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> resistance leader Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> says peace talks opening Feb. 19 will fail because the pro-Vietnamese government in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> has imposed unacceptable conditions, the resistance radio reported Monday. The Voice of the Khmer, monitored in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, quoted <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> as saying government opposition to deploying an international peace-keeping force in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> would allow the return of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> regime, which killed hundreds of thousands of people in 1975-78. The Phnom Penh government, which <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> installed after invading the country in December 1978, also rejected <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>'s demand that it be dismantled and join a provisional government that would supervise a general election. These issues are to be discussed at a second round of peace talks planned for <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>'s capital, <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>, starting Sunday. The talks will bring together communist <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>; the Cambodian government of Premier <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>, and the three-party resistance coalition, including <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>'s group; the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, and the non-communist <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> of former Cambodian Premier Son <PERSON> Sann </PERSON>. Other Southeast Asian nations also will take part. According to the resistance radio, <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> recently said in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> that the talks `` would not be successful because the resistance forces can not just submit themselves to the Vietnamese colonialist regime as required by <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>'s conditions.'' <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> `` affirmed that more than anything else, he wants peace for the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> people,'' the broadcast said. `` But peace without independence is worthless.'' <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> has said he will not attend the <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION> talks because <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> rejected his peace proposals. But his son Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Ranariddh </PERSON> will represent him. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, widely expected to take a leading role in any future Cambodian government, is at his home in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The Chinese arm the resistance against the Soviet-supplied Vietnamese. The radio said the prince had no plans to meet President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who visits <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> late this month, or with Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who is due there in mid-May. But <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> said he was ready to meet them anytime, if asked, the broadcast said. A Thai army official meanwhile disclosed Monday that more than 7,000 Cambodian refugees who were evacuated from two Khmer Rouge-run camps because of heavy shelling from across the Cambodian border have returned to their camps at Ta <PERSON> Luan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Borai </PERSON>, just inside <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>. Much of the shelling that peaked in mid-November was directed at an area just inside eastern <LOCATION> Trat </LOCATION> province, where the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> had herded about 7,000 refugees, apparently to prepare to populate strategic areas of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. Gunners in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> continued to pound <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>