d. She said the utility has written a letter to plant personnel asking for help in the investigation, but so far has identified no suspects. It was possible the seals had been damaged by accident, she said, but emphasized the company was proceeding on the assumption it was vandalism. If a suspect is identified, he or she would be subject to federal criminal charges, Ms. <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> was informed of the incident, but was not actively involved in the case, she said. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> sent an inspector to the plant after the discovery, but was now monitoring the utility's internal investigation. Ms. <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> said she did not expect the incident to hold up the restart of the 850-megawatt Unit 2, which was shut down for refueling at the end of January and should be back on line after 12 weeks. She also said the incident was not considered serious enough to cause a change in safety procedures at the plant.
