<HEAD>Central American Summit Quickly Bogs Down Over Democracy Measures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with squabble bogging down summit, quotes,
other. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SAL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COSTA DEL SOL, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A summit of the five Central American presidents bogged down on opening day Monday in a dispute involving <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and at least two other nations over how to appraise progress toward democracy. An adviser to the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> said earlier Monday that <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> was making strong democratic commitments because it believes the rebel movement is dead. `` With the Contras' military defeat and the passing of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, the external military threat to the <LOCATION> Nicaraguan </LOCATION> government that impeded democratization is gone,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Reichler </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> lawyer employed by <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> as an adviser and representative. Later, however, foreign ministers <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Escoto </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Acevedo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> clashed publicly over whether commissions to monitor progress toward democracy should include Central Americans or foreign participants. `` We have the moral authority to select a commission of Central Americans. We should carry out our own verification,'' <PERSON> Acevedo </PERSON> told a news conference. `` It seems to us somewhat anti-democratic that it should be we ourselves who appraise our own actions,'' <PERSON> D'Escoto </PERSON> told a separate news conference. The two spoke as presidents <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Vinicio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cerezo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> worked in closed session late into the first day of a two-day summit. <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> reportedly was siding with <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> in the dispute. `` They're going at each other quite harshly,'' said a member of the Nicaraguan delegation, commenting on condition of anonymity. The meeting intends to breathe new life into the stalled <LOCATION> Esquipulas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> II </LOCATION> plan designed to promote peace and demcoracy in the region. Since the presidents signed the accord in August 1987, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s regional partners _ especially <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> _ have criticized <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> for what they alleged is an authoritarian Sandinista regime. `` The political problem in the region is one of democracy _ of totalitarianism versus liberty,'' <PERSON> Acevedo </PERSON> said. Officials with the Nicaraguan delegation said <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> proposed a bilateral agreement with <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> that calls for the estimated 11,000-strong Contra force there to be disbanded. The Contras fled to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> after <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid expired last year. Under the proposal, the Contras could take advantage of an amnesty offered by the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> or go to third countries under the supervision of international organizations. The Sandinistas would release the estimated 3,500 Contras and former Nicaraguan national guardsmen now in Sandinista prisons. The officials said <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> presented the plan to <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> at the Feb. 2 inauguration of Venezuelan President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>. The five presidents first appeared encouraged by the mere fact of being under the same roof after six months of delay. The summit was rescheduled and postponed five times. `` I am sure that we, with optimism, will analyze efforts we've made according to <LOCATION> Esquipulas </LOCATION> II and search for favorable solutions that will promote peace and progress in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> said as the meeting began All the chief executives except <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, in a green army uniform, wore casual attire fitting the climate of this seaside resort 40 miles southeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. They had intended to mark the anniversary of the signing with a summit in August, but could not agree on an agenda. After some initial success, the <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> plan stalled last year. Officials said the summit's principal subject would be enforcing compliance with the injunction against using one signatory's territory as a base for attacking another, but the presidents disagree on verification mechanisms <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> is said to favor a commission of Central Americans, but Nicaraguan officials said their government wants the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> and human rights groups included on such a panel. All the presidents expressed support for the framework constructed last week by their foreign ministers in talks with <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>. The ministers want `` an impartial mechanism'' created for on-site verification of compliance. The tentative idea is to form an observer group from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>, the 1987 Nobel Peace laureate, said the summit would `` re-establish our credibility with the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people and the entire world.'' A decade of civil conflict and economic depression have transformed the region of 25 million people into a zone of turbulence. An estimated 160,000 people have been killed in wars in a decade and most Central Americans live in extreme poverty. Civil wars still plague <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> but the scale has been reduced greatly in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>. The Contras signed a preliminary cease-fire with the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> last March but <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s government stands accused of failing to make good its pledge to strengthen democratic institutions and practices. <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, the Marxist-led insurgent army, announced a two-day truce for the meeting.
