<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Water Tank Art, Adv 15,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, Feb. 15 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX7 of Feb. 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Water Tank Sculptures Capture Disappearing City Scene</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When archaeologists dig up <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>' sculptures centuries from now, they'll find clues to yet another era that has gone down the drain. In the past month, the 35-year-old artist has created some 20 terra cotta water tanks, ranging from 2 inches to 2 feet. To <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, it's a way of commemorating the real-life rooftop towers, which to her resemble monuments to the industrial age. `` I'm a child of the city and think there is a lot of beauty to be found in the city's ugliness,'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. But the artist's models have been disappearing, with demolition teams casting them them off the city's skyline faster than she can cast them in clay. The rooftop tanks have been here since the late 1800s, when the city was rebuilding from the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Fire of 1871. They were put on the high-rises of the time, buildings more than several stories high. The filled tanks improved water pressure and served as resevoirs from which to draw during emergencies. They were a craft in themselves, at first made like wooden barrels with tongue-and-groove seams so perfect that no extra seal was needed to hold the water. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> found the models for her art in a changing industrial area on <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Near </LOCATION> <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>. She drove there on another errand late last year and decided to get out of her car and tour on foot. `` There was a whole vista of them,'' she said. She photographed some, sketched others. She studied the tanks, trying to decide what techniques and materials she could use to reproduce the ladders, capture the colors and portray the peeling paint and weathered wood. Then, in her studio, she began constructing them, throwing clay on a potter's wheel and adding hand-built parts for tops, stilts and buildings. She fired them in a kiln and chose 10 for the show, naming some for streets where she'd seen the real tanks. But by the time the exhibit opened Jan. 20, three of the real tanks had been knocked down. `` Better water pumps have negated their use,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Acker </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Plumbing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Contractors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Insurance companies still discount premiums for buildings with tanks because the reservoirs provide extra protection, <PERSON> Acker </PERSON> said. But a wave of housing rehabilitation work in recent years is hastening the demise of the vessels. Old factories with tanks are being converted into town houses with more modern plumbing. Old schools are being gutted for lofts, and old housing is being made to look newer. `` Progress,'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, her exhibit will continue this month at the <ORGANIZATION> Lill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gallery </ORGANIZATION>, a studio, gallery and ceramics school housed in a building that was a horse barn when <PERSON> Lill </PERSON> <PERSON> Street </PERSON> was at the edge of the city and at the end of the trolley line. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, a teacher at the school, says so far people seem to be intrigued by the show. `` It looks stark,'' she said. `` It looks like a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> cityscape. ...'' The way it used to be.
</TEXT>
