<SECOND>PM-Walter Mears, ADV 14,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tues Feb 14 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Kinder, Gentler Cliche</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Kindly, gently, and, it seems interminably, the phrase that became a <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> cliche is being used for him, against him and all around him. The president spared it another repetition in what amounted to his State of the Union address Thursday night _ he spoke of decency, compassion, generosity, government that helps people, but he skipped `` kinder and gentler.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was one of the few orators who did. `` A kinder, gentler <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>?'' House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> response to the president. `` That's the old time Democratic religion. We embrace it enthusiastically.'' There is the matter of agreeing on what it means. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said words and gestures wo n't do _ it will cost money. By Democratic reckoning, considerably more money than <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposes to spend. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> finds the phrase a handy one. `` Obviously this is not a kinder, gentler budget,'' the speaker said when President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> sent <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> his farewell spending proposal. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> adjusted spending priorities, notably by reducing the proposed <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget, but Democrats still used the K word and the G word to criticize his proposal. `` He's offering a minimum down payment on a kinder, gentler <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` But I ca n't see how he's proposing to meet the necessary installment payments. They might have to repossess his kinder, gentler <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> for failure to meet the payments.'' But <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget director, said the new administration's budget would, too, make the nation kinder and gentler, although perhaps not as rapidly as everyone would like. Kinder and gentler than the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration? `` Well, I'm not saying that,'' <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> replied. He said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> budget seeks more money for education, environmental cleanups, aid to the homeless, Medicaid for the needy and like programs. `` If they are marks of a ... kinder, gentler society, then it meets that test. ...'' Democratic National Chairman <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> quickly joined the oratorical game. Praising the achievements of Democratic governors, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said `` for these leaders, kinder and gentler does n't come from the pen of some ghost writer. It comes from the heart.'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, installed last Friday, said the next time the administration says `` we need leadership that's kinder and gentler, I'm going to ask kinder and gentler than whom? The Republican Party?'' In 1992, chimed in <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, speaker of the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, `` we will capture the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and give this nation a kinder and gentler leader.'' That crop of Ks and Gs represents only the tip of the cliche. It covers usage by a handful of political spokesmen since last Thursday. A check of <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> files turned up 140 stories using the phrase since the Nov. 8 election. It has become fodder for TV comics, promising kinder and gentler one-liners. On Groundhog Day, forecasts were for another six weeks of a kinder and gentler winter. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> used his own line repeatedly during the presidential campaign _ startling his strategists one night when he said he'd be kinder and gentler, and would stop negative campaigning against Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. By morning, he had decided otherwise. In conversation, trying to remember a man's name, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> described him as a kinder and gentler looking fellow. In the inaugural address, he declared a mission `` to make kinder the face of the nation and gentler the face of the world.'' All of this flowed from a passage in his acceptance speech last Aug. 18 at the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION>, crafted by campaign speechwriter <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Noonan </PERSON>, who should have signed up for royalties on use of the line. `` The fact is prosperity has a purpose,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` It is to allow us to pursue the better angels, to give us time to think and grow. Prosperity with a purpose means taking your idealism and making it concrete by certain acts of goodness. It means helping a child from an unhappy home learn how to read ... It means teaching troubled children through your presence that there's such a thing as reliable love. Some would say it's soft and insufficiently tough to care about these things. But where is it written that we must act as if we do not care, as if we are not moved? `` Well I am moved,'' he said. `` I want a kinder, gentler nation.'' That's the line that stuck, outlasting the cryptic thousand points of light turned on in the same speech. But after six months, it might be kinder and gentler to dream up a new catch phrase.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
