<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs Feb. 22 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Greek Cypriots Openin a University; Turks Already Have One</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After years of delay, the <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> community is founding a university in an effort to halt an exodus of talented students and help reunify the war-divided <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island. But when the <ORGANIZATION> Cyprus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> opens next year, it will be competing for international recognition with a 3-year-old Turkish Cypriot university also seeking to become a prestigious higher education center. Although Greek and <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> educators say they want students from both communities, the island's long-running political problems make that unlikely. `` Our university will teach in both <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> and Turkish, and there'll be a department of Turkish studies,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cypriot </ORGANIZATION> education minister, <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Philippou </PERSON>, said in an interview. `` We want it to contribute to reuniting <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. We hope Turkish Cypriots will attend, but it depends on the political situation.'' Professor <PERSON> Okan </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarhan </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mediterranean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> at </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Famagusta </ORGANIZATION> in the Turkish Cypriot republic in northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, said: `` We have students from 17 countries but no Greek Cypriots.'' <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> was unofficially partitioned in 1974 when the Turkish army invaded after an Athens-inspired coup intended to unite the island with <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. The breakaway Turkish Cypriot statelet was proclaimed in 1983 in the northern one-third of the island occupied by the Turkish forces. Reunification talks between Greek and Turkish Cypriot leaders on a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> Nation-proposed bi-zonal federation resumed last fall after a three-year break but have bogged down amid traditional differences. Some Greek Cypriot officials fear that the de facto partition of the island will harden as time goes by, with new generations growing up on both sides with no contact with each other. `` <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> is a tiny place, but there's a great hunger for higher education,'' said <PERSON> Margit </PERSON> <PERSON> Schatzman </PERSON>, an American educational consultant preparing a study on the <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> universities. `` Both the Greek and Turkish Cypriot institutions are structuring their programs along mainstream Western university lines. It's clear they're both looking for international status,'' she said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>. Education Minister <PERSON> Philippou </PERSON>, a former mathematics professor at <ORGANIZATION> Patras </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, said the university plan was drawn up in three months last summer by a group of politicians and <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> academics, including professors at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and British universities `` The decision to have a university was taken almost 20 years ago but never implemented,'' he said. `` Now it must happen if we're to stop losing good people who go abroad to study.'' The Greek Cypriot university is due to open in 1990 in temporary premises with 400 students and 30 faculty and eventually grow to 4,000 students and 330 faculty members. It is budgeted to cost $ 42 million. The planners say that having a local university will save a large chunk of an estimated $ 24 million spent every year on sending 10,000 Cypriots to <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION>, British and American universities. Many start careers overseas because, with more than 50,000 graduates among the 480,000 Greek Cypriots, jobs at home are hard to find at home. The government offers free business courses to recent graduates to make them employable in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>' booming service economy, but `` with our own university we can channel people where they're needed by offering development-related courses,'' <PERSON> Philippou </PERSON> said. Young Greek Cypriots say they welcome a university because it will make <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION> livelier as well as saving family funds. `` The university will bring lots of activities, there'll be more music and cultural activities. I'm looking forward to it,'' said <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> Palaiologou </PERSON>, who wants to study management. The <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cypriot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> will decide whether some courses should be taught in English. But with a business school planned, that may be essential to attract first-rate staff and students, several educators said. The <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mediterranean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, where courses are taught in English, has a problem because it is in the Turkish Cypriot republic, which is recognized only by <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. `` We're an international university, but we do n't qualify for aid from any international organization,'' said <PERSON> Tarhan </PERSON>, the university's head `` I think that's unfair since we're an educational institution and not involved in politics.'' Foreigners from Arab countries, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> make up around 10 percent of its 2,300 students. The rest are Turks and Turkish Cypriots, but they also may spend a year taking intensive English classes before starting as freshmen. East Mediterranean, a former junior technical college upgraded to a university in 1986, focuses on engineering and economics. <PERSON> Tarhan </PERSON> said a business school will open and more humanities courses will be offered in the next two years.
</TEXT>
