<HEAD>NEW YORK _ ``Black and Blue''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 When the brothers appeared in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> movies in the'40s, choreographer <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Castle </PERSON> thought up `` mad tricks'' for the pair to do, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Castle </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> wrote and directed `` Tap.'' Most of the tappers had to take other jobs during the lean years, said <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Tang </PERSON>, 73, who choreographed `` Tap'' and most of `` Black and Blue.'' <PERSON> Honi </PERSON> <PERSON> Coles </PERSON> weathered those years working at the Apollo Theater. <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> spent the'50s working in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Tang </PERSON>, who always loved to teach, opened a tap school when he was 20. `` Tap was my love,'' <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Tang </PERSON> said. When its popularity waned, he choreographed nightclub acts and, for seven years, TV's `` The <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> Show.'' Fifteen-year-old <PERSON> Savion </PERSON> <PERSON> Glover </PERSON>, a tap prodigy as were the <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brothers </PERSON>, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Rooney </PERSON>, absorbs every style of tap, <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Tang </PERSON> said. `` The older dancers call him ` the little sponge,''' hs said. `` As he keeps getting more spectacular, his own style will start to come out. It is beginning to happen and will continue to happen.'' All the older tappers seem to have nicknames. `` I have n't heard my real name in I do n't know when,'' <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Slyde </PERSON>, who's in both `` Tap'' and `` Black and Blue,'' specialized in sliding <PERSON> Bunny </PERSON> <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON>, 66, with his saucer eyes and Bambi-like lashes, dances in both `` Tap'' and `` Black and Blue.'' He got his nickname from his grandmother because when she'd come home from work, <PERSON> Bunny </PERSON> would quickly scoot to get her slippers. `` I danced as soon as I was born,'' he said. `` When I saw <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> dance, I knew I wanted to be a dancer. He sanctioned it.'' <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON> tapped with big bands as a visual addition and an added rhythm instrument. The earliest forms of tap dancing can be found centuries ago in parts of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. It was further distilled in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by African slaves and the immigrants who brought their clog dancing with them to the new world. Tap started its current escalation on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION> in 1971, when `` No, No, <PERSON> Nanette </PERSON>'' was revived. `` Eubie!'' came to <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Eubie </PERSON> <PERSON> Blake </PERSON>, whose music it comprised wanted <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> and <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Hines </PERSON> in it, recalling them from the act they had with their father called <PERSON> Hines </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hines </PERSON> and Dad. The brothers went on to do `` <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellington </PERSON>'s Sophisticated Ladies.'' <PERSON> Alfonso </PERSON> <PERSON> Riberio </PERSON> originated the title role in `` The Tap Dance Kid'' and the names of tappers such as <PERSON> Hinton </PERSON> Battle and <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> <PERSON> Burge </PERSON> got known around Broadway for that show and `` Sophisticated Ladies.'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reams </PERSON> brought Astaire-style tapping to `` 42nd Street.'' <PERSON> Honi </PERSON> <PERSON> Coles </PERSON> won a <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> as best supporting actor in a musical in `` My One and Only.'' <PERSON> Patti </PERSON> <PERSON> LuPone </PERSON> taps today in the revival of `` Anything Goes.'' Upcoming are Broadway musicals in which <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Tune </PERSON> works with the <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rhythm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kings </ORGANIZATION> and one in which <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Hines </PERSON> plays, choreographs and dances as pianist-composer <PERSON> Jelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Roll </PERSON> <PERSON> Morton </PERSON>, allowing tap to signify music. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Tang </PERSON> is confident that tap will resume its proper position in the arts. In the meantime, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tap </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> is underway in <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, giving the dance form an even greater credibility. A project of the Colorado Dance Festival, the association has started receiving inquiries from producers looking for tappers.
