<FIRST>s a BC-APN--HomelessHero Adv26-1stAdd   02-13 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Homeless Hero, Adv 26-1st Add,0785</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sun., Feb. 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: homeless invisible.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Two urges are at odds. The urge to create a democracy _ the urge that made people live in communities and rebuild barns _ and economics, the urge toward competition and individualism and greed. One implies charity and generosity. The other says to hell with the community, create your own niche. `` The negative side has become dominant. But the other side nags at us. We're such a sophisticated, fast-paced society, just getting through the day is task enough. We have become a frightened, neurotic people. We drug ourselves to make reality a little softer. Our families are falling apart. Our schools are breaking down. `` We have createdrld.'' <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> walked away from middle-class <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in 1969, after waking up one night `` literally in a cold sweat.'' A high school dropo an unnatural wout who sold washing machines before talking his way into a high-paying job as an executive recruiter, <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> got married and had two children before he realized he was n't cut out to be a family man. He set out to find himself and wound up in federal prison on an auto-theft charge. While serving time at <LOCATION> Danbury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, he got to know <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Berrigan </PERSON>, in prison for destroying draft records. <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> joined the two priests' anti-war group, made up of prisoneviolent protest, and read a book a day for 2 -LCB- years. After his release in 1972, <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> joined an anti-war group in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, then moved to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> a year later to join CCNV. In time, he says, `` Homelessness became the domestic counterpart to what was happening in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. In 1975, the war had ended. In the house I was living in, we were dealing with evictions of families. We opened up our living room to people.'' Over the years, the seam between <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON>'s life and his work has disappeared. `` The deeper you go in, the more you understand the symbols,'' he says. Identifying and exploiting those symbols _ tearing down fences, both literally and figuratively _ is the key to <ORGANIZATION> CCNV </ORGANIZATION>'s agenda of civil disobedience. `` Our acts are very Old Testament,'' he says. `` We're dealing with symbols and images. Fasting reminds people that real lives are at stake. Symbols like fences are very emotionally charged. Property that exists only to hurt others has no right to exist.'' <ORGANIZATION> Snyder </ORGANIZATION>'s adversaries have found the hunger strikes particularly antagonizing, such as his 1978 fast in an attempt to force a wealthy <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> church in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to contribute to the CCNV shelter fund. `` It was like having a gun pointed at my head,'' recalls the Rev. James English. English refused, and eventually, close to death, <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> abandoned the fast. `` I do n't do these things to get people upset, but I have no qualms about upsetting people,'' <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> says. `` When people begin to feel, they begin to think.'' Within the homeless movement, where nothing remotely approaching consensus has emerged, <ORGANIZATION> Snyder </ORGANIZATION> is not without critics. Detractors have portrayed him as self-serving and publicity-hungry. Some call him `` Hollywood <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON>.'' The $ 5 million it took to renovate the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> shelter upset some advocates, including <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprowal </PERSON>, a former hospital workers union organizer. `` How many houses could you build for that kind of money? How many people could you put to work with that kind of money?'' <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> acknowledges that overnight shelter is a temporary answer. `` The long-term is adequate housing. The real solution is a society that's not built on never-ending consumption. But no more shelters is a barbaric thought.'' The Hollywood reference sprung from a made-for-TV movie that glossed over <ORGANIZATION> Snyder </ORGANIZATION>'s abandonment of his family and zeroed in on his good deeds. That <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheen </PERSON>, who played <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON>, called him `` a saint'' did n't help. <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> steadfastly refuses to watch the film and squirms when asked about it. A soft-spoken man who professes to be uncomfortable in the spotlight, he also has a talent for making the most of it. The movie, `` Samaritan: The <ORGANIZATION> Mitch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Snyder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Story </ORGANIZATION>,'' added $ 150,000 to the movement's war chest. Besides, <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> discovered <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> long ago. It was only a matter of time before <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> discovered him. `` The three biggest influences on my life were all movies: ` Mr. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> Goes to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,' ` It's a Wonderful Life,' and ` A Christmas <PERSON> Carol </PERSON>.' `` They taught me the lessons of my life: that good will always overcome evil, and that the most insignificant person can make a difference, provided what he's doing is right.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 26</NOTE>
