<SECOND>BC-APN--Chicago Election, Adv 26-2 Takes,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: To be mailed to subscribers next week.)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ Chicagoans go to the polls this week in a special mayoral election to decide who will serve the last two years of the second term of the late <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, the city's first black mayor. The leading candidates are two blacks hoping to win over <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s supporters and the son of the longtime political boss <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The ghosts of two former mayors are hovering over the campaign trail as voters in the nation's third-largest city decide who will lead them into the 1990s. Long gone is the late Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, a boss of the old school, who used concentrated political muscle to run <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> for 21 years before his death in 1976. But the front-runner in the special Democratic mayoral primary is one of his sons, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, the 46-year-old <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> state's attorney whose blood ties to City Hall legend sometimes seem to transcend his own record. Gone as well is <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, the city's first black mayor, whose death on Nov. 25, 1987, set the stage for this year's special election. But his legacy of leadership is a key issue for black voters being wooed by Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, 54, <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s chief primary rival, and <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, 45, who is running a third-party campaign on the `` Harold <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'' ticket. At stake in the special mayoral contest are the last two years of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s second term. In the Democratic primary, <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> also face <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON>, a white alderman who supported <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and two lagging candidates. Three Republicans _ none well known in this Democratic stronghold _ were on the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> ballot. After the Feb. 28 primary elections, <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> will take on the winners in the April 4 general election. This campaign season, in a city known for its deep racial divisions, black voters who united behind <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> are being ardently courted by <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>. Neither can supplant the affable, streetwise <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, who has become a symbol of change and unity for many Chicagoans. `` <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> ... embodied all of the hopes and aspirations of a generation of people who genuinely believed that <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> was ready for reform,'' said Cook County Recorder of Deeds <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Moseley </PERSON> <PERSON> Braun </PERSON>, who last fall became the first black to win a major county office. Five weeks before the primary, <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> _ elected by the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to succeed <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> _ finally won the endorsement of civil rights leader and presidential contender <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` He has done more than any of his primary opponents to sustain the <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> coalition,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. But the delay in that long-awaited endorsement underscores the discord in the black community since <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s death. And <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> declined to say where he would stand if <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> faced <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> in the general election. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, who served as <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s floor leader in the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, is campaigning as the late mayor's heir apparent. His withdrawal from the Democratic primary prevented a split in the black vote that would have virtually guaranteed <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> the nomination. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s endorsement was a matter of great concern to both black candidates, but some observers say it wo n't help <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>. A massive black turnout is <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>'s only chance in the primary, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleppner </PERSON>, author of `` <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Divided: The Making of a Black Mayor'' and director of the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in De <PERSON> Kalb </PERSON>. `` My suspicion is that he -LRB- <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> -RRB- is going to get the overwhelming bulk of the black vote, with moderate turnout _ and that wo n't be enough,'' he said. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> still has `` the image that he was put in there by the white aldermen,'' <PERSON> Kleppner </PERSON> said, referring to the role of longtime <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> foes in engineering <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>'s election over <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> as acting mayor in December 1987. `` Time heals a lot of wounds,'' counters <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s former political office director, who endorsed <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and predicts a strong black turnout for him. The racial breakdown of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s voting-age population on July 1 was about 46.8 percent white, 38.3 percent black and 14.9 percent Hispanic, said <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bousfield </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s city demographer.
