<HEAD>CHICAGO: city demographer.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 In 1983, black voters turned out in force to support <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in the primary, giving him 36 percent of the vote and a stunning victory over then-Mayor <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> yrne and <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, who divided the white vote. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> went on to a narrow victory in a racially charged general-election fight against little-known Republican <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Epton </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kleppner </PERSON> said he believes the racism that marked the 1983 mayoral contest remains, but `` it's under the rug.'' Racism was tempered when the city actually had a black mayor, he said, and many white voters feel <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> is a shoo-in. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s status as front-runner has not been hurt by virtually citywide recognition of the family name. `` Bring back the <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> dynasty!'' supporters cheer at some campaign stops. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> _ and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> _ came up through the ranks of the `` machine,'' the patronage-rich political organization <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s father built <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> says little about his father, whose last years in office were marred by the riots at the 1968 Democratic National Convention and other controversies. He cites his own record as county prosecutor and a state senator. `` The politics and name-calling are tearing <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> apart when we need to work together,'' <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> told a civic club meeting. `` I'm not interested in being ` the white candidate,' or in serving as mayor for half the people.'' <PERSON> Kleppner </PERSON> says <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> will win the primary if he avoids the kind of slip that could provide a focal point for black opposition. He adds that such a slip is unlikely since <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> `` has been very well scripted.'' <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> kept to that script in a television debate earlier this month with <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON>. Repeatedly baited by <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON> _ who at one point said his supporters thought <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> was the `` great white hope'' _ <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> refused to spar. City jobs and minority hiring are hot topics and <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, boasting that a quarter of city contracts are going to minorities, contends <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s election would mean moving backward. Aides say <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> has a good affirmative action record in his office, more than doubling the number of black lawyers there in eight years. Activist <PERSON> Lu </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> said he's not convinced. `` No white mayor has ever been sensitive to the needs of our people,'' he said. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> may benefit from black-Jewish tension lingering after the furor last spring over tape-recorded lectures by <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cokely </PERSON> that contained anti-Semitic remarks. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> waited five days to fire Cokely. A few hours before the announcement, <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> denounced <PERSON> Cokely </PERSON>'s remarks as `` inappropriate.'' There are many Jews among the white `` lakefront liberals'' who helped elect <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` I do n't think that either black mayoral candidate played an exemplary role in the Cokely affair,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> of the local Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith. There have been other tussles. Days after becoming mayor, <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> faced the disclosure that as an alderman years before, he accepted what he called a finder's fee of $ 30,000 for helping a lawyer obtain a bank loan. In another case, he admitted filing income tax returns late, though no money was owed the government. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, meanwhile, was questioned about a report that petitions circulated for a failed 1986 referendum to make the mayor's race non-partisan may have included fraudulent signatures linked to workers in his office. He cooled the issue by calling for appointment of a special prosecutor. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> says the winner of the Democratic primary is sure to be mayor, but <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> demonstrated considerable strength when he submitted more than 100,000 signatures in filing for his third-party bid _ four times the required number. <PERSON> Kleppner </PERSON> suggests it does n't much matter who wins. With the 1991 regularly scheduled mayoral race coming up soon after this spring's special election, the winner will begin campaigning immediately, he said. `` What this city needs it's not going to get from any of the candidates,'' <PERSON> Kleppner </PERSON> said, `` and that's long-range planning.''
