<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` The Stars We Are'' -LRB- Capitol -RRB- _ <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Almond </PERSON> <PERSON> When </PERSON> was the last time you heard lyrics like these? `` I'll be a dragonfly, a butterfly, A secret or a little lie to test you, A song a verse a lullaby, A symphony ...'' `` In my hands the grains of sand, A thousand million moments of emotion _ Oh these my dreams are yours.'' `` I'm a teardrop in a storm, A storm at the end of the world.'' Set words like these to a rock beat and add strings, trumpets and other lush instrumentation, backing vocals with plenty of atmospheric reverb, and an occasional spoken-word passage. What do you have? <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON>? The <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blues </ORGANIZATION>? King Crimson? No, this is not a lost 1967 recording of early Art Rock. But <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Almond </PERSON> and his group, <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magia </ORGANIZATION>, exhibit a youthful romanticism that has been missing from rock since the <ORGANIZATION> Flower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> days. That's refreshing as a break from the current formulas, a revitalization of an almost extinct style. And it's reassuring to know that even in the late'80s a songwriter can refer to himself as someone `` who is afraid of getting jaded.'' But youthful romanticism and idealism can lead to youthful excess, and this record is often both trite and overwrought in its efforts to achieve poetry. In a song called `` The Very Last Pearl,'' Almond aptly sings, `` Call me romantic, Call me deluded.'' He concludes another song by drawing out the phrase, `` And I ... a fool ... for love!'' Really, now. Amid such excess, however, there are some good songs on this album. `` Only the Moment'' and `` Tears Run Rings'' in particular stand out as well-realized pop songs that manage to escape being overdone. All it takes is a little restraint. _ By <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Wall of Pride'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Howlers </PERSON> <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> and the Howlers play the kind of loud, rowdy rock' n' roll that sounds best late at night in a noisy, crowded bar. That does n't mean you have to invite a bunch of strangers over to your apartment and throw beer bottles against the wall to enjoy `` Wall of Pride,'' the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> band's second album. But make no mistake, it's party music all the way. Transferring such bar-band energy to a record is no easy task but producer <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Manning </PERSON>, who has worked with blues-rockers Z.Z. Top and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorogood </PERSON>, has a way with this sort of thing. The focus is not on the songs, which are good if not overly distinctive, as much as the sound itself, especially the sandpaper growl of lead singer <PERSON> Omar </PERSON>, who also plays a raw, scraping guitar. He's helped by a strong rhythm section and keyboard player <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Scortia </PERSON>, who apparently is n't afraid to occasionally use his elbows instead of his fingers to pound the piano. The album's two cover songs are interesting: a remake of the Animals' `` We Got ta Get Out of This Place,'' which abandons any pretense to the subtlety of the original; and a version of <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>'s `` Down in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>,'' recorded in an odd, muffled sound that recalls the great bluesman's loping style. The originals, most of which are written or co-written by an otherwise unidentified <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dykes </PERSON>, range from the all-out boogie of `` Rattlesnake Shake'' to the rhythm and blues-flavored `` King's Ransom. That's not a very far range, but these guys do n't claim to be Renaissance men. They're Howlers. _ By <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
