<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Feb 24-26 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: Two Titans Consider ``The University''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakeshott </PERSON> is 87 years old, lives in a stone cottage in <LOCATION> Dorset </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, and is, in the minds of many, one of the century's great philosophers. <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> <PERSON> Giamatti </PERSON>, a teacher of Italian, English and comparative literature, was president of <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and is about to become the commissioner of baseball in April. The two men, seemingly so distant in place and circumstance, are actually close intellectual neighbors. By happy coincidence, each has just published collections of essays describing their views on education and the idea of the university. Both have fashioned elegantly written defenses of liberal education and the ideal of the university as a place of civil conversation; a place where, as <PERSON> Oakeshott </PERSON> puts it, a student may `` come to seek his intellectual fortune'' undistracted by the press of time or outside worries. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> Learning: <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakeshott </PERSON> on Education'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, $ 20 -RRB- was edited by <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> and a friend and unabashed admirer of the British philosopher who is professor emeritus at the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Giamatti </PERSON>'s `` A Free and Ordered Space: The Real World of the University'' -LRB- <PERSON> W.W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Norton </PERSON>, $ 19.95 -RRB- consists of 23 essays, many of them originally delivered as speeches at commencements or convocations. The Oakeshott collection, in particular, represents a welcome rescue operation, an opportunity for Americans to discover a major British philosopher and teacher of enormous wit, charm and modesty. His essays add a civilizing voice to the current school reform debate. For universities and their supporters, the two collections could n't be more timely. Taken together, they represent a forceful rebuttal to `` The Closing of the American Mind,'' the curmudgeonly best seller by <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> political scientist <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON> which charged American higher education with selling out its intellectual responsibilities to 1960s hooliganism. The introductions in both collections leave no doubt that <PERSON> Oakeshott </PERSON> and <PERSON> Giamatti </PERSON> are aiming straight at such Bloom-and-doomsayers. <PERSON> Giamatti </PERSON>, for one, blames his academic colleagues for their silence under siege, and urges them to make their mission better understood to an increasingly impatient public. `` A parent who hungers to know, for instance, why a child's college experience costs so much or, worse, has seemed so unsatisfactory or lacking in connectedness with anything in the past will have heard very little from higher education about its issues or its problems,'' <PERSON> Giamatti </PERSON> writes `` Small wonder that <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON>'s book is a best seller.'' <PERSON> Oakeshott </PERSON>'s essays are more difficult, both intellectually and for their use of British idiom. The collection includes some of <PERSON> Oakeshott </PERSON>'s least-known works, some of which appeared as much as 40 years ago only in out-of-print journals. Over the years, <PERSON> Oakeshott </PERSON> has acquired a small but devoted army of academtic adherents. He is perhaps best known for his definitive introduction to <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hobbes </PERSON>' `` Leviathan.'' But his other works, notably `` Experience and Its Modes,'' and `` Rationalism in Politics,'' have become bibles for those who have watched with horror the rise of social science and technocracy on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> campuses at the expense of history and the humanities. <PERSON> Oakeshott </PERSON> describes the university as an idea, more than a place _ a community where scholars, teachers and pupils engage each other in ceaseless skepticism. Universities are, and must remain, blessedly `` useless'' beyond the enjoyment of learning they offer participants. His essays, including several in the present collection, also constitute a powerful defense of political conservatism and have thus been quoted regularly by columnists such as <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON>. Yet Oakeshott himself has always been far more good-natured in his views than those who have most often invoked his name. Still, practical-minded Americans often find a number of his beliefs difficult to swallow. For example, he describes the undergraduate as `` not a child, not a beginner. He has already had his schooling elsewhere, and has learned enough, morally and intellectually, to take a chance with himself upon the open sea ...'' That description might seem a bit elitist to some, leaving little room in the modern university for remediation. Further, <PERSON> Oakeshott </PERSON> completely and defiantly rejects utilitarian justifications for higher education: `` The current talk about the ` mission' and the ` function' of a university goes rather over my head,'' he writes. `` It assumes that there is something called ` a university,' a contrivance of some sort, something you could make another of tomorrow if you had enough money, of which it is sensible to ask, ` What is it for?''' Or again: `` A university ... has a place in the society to which it belongs, but that place is not the function of contributing to some other kind of activity in the society but of being itself and not another thing.'' The historian of Oakeshottian bent, for example, practices history for its own sake, not for its supposed `` lessons'' or other real or imagined uses. Viewed in purely practical terms, <PERSON> Oakeshott </PERSON>'s scholar does n't give a hoot about whether his activity is of use, except insofar as it is interesting to him He wants to understand for understanding's sake. <PERSON> Giamatti </PERSON>, as a former university president, is far more willing to explore scholarship's connections with other segments of society. But his central view of the university as a `` free and open space'' is remarkably compatible with the Oakeshott ideal. `` Its essence,'' <PERSON> Giamatti </PERSON> writes, `` is that give-and-take, that civil conversation in its innumerable forms. When that conversation, the to-and-fro of ideas, is stymied or foreclosed or frozen, when the questing for truth is told that it must cease because there is only one Truth and it is Complete, then the institution in its essence is chilled and its life threatened.'' In an essay titled `` The Earthly Use of a <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Giamatti </PERSON> confronts an all-too-American challenge to higher learning: <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> education `` is all very well, but how does someone make a living with this joy of learning and pleasure in the pursuit of learning? What is the earthly use of all this kind of education later on, in the practical, real world? `` These are not trivial questions, though the presuppositions behind them puzzle me somewhat. I am puzzled, for instance, by the unexamined assumption that the ` real world' is always thought to lie outside or beyond the realm of education. I am puzzled by those who think that ideas do not have reality or that knowledge is irrelevant to the workings of daily life.'' It's comforting to know that such thoughts still occupy the man who might adjudicate baseball's balk rule come next Spring.
</TEXT>
