<HEAD>Washington's Birthday Key Ritual In American Culture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It may seem like just a day off, but next Monday marks a key ritual for affirming the nation's identity by linking up to a legend. With its ancestor worship and retelling of myths, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s Birthday serves the cultural purpose of instructing the young and reminding grown-ups about what it is to be an American, social science experts say `` He was in a way an ideal American, and so in celebrating his birthday the society celebrates itself. It is important for society to do that because in this way it reinforces its values,'' said <PERSON> Liah </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenfeld </PERSON>, an assistant professor of sociology and social studies at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` American identity for the most part begins with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kertzer </PERSON>, an anthropology professor at <ORGANIZATION> Bowdoin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. He is `` the point of reference -LRB- for -RRB- what it means to be an American.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> was born Feb. 22, 1732, but the federal observance falls on Feb. 20 this year. Some states combine the holiday with <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>'s Feb. 12 birthday and call it Presidents Day. Ancestor worship, is common in the world's cultures, the experts said. Enshrining heroes in myths is a way `` of really providing our own identity by attaching ourselves to a past that is larger than life ... To do that we have to regularly have some ritual observances to keep those myths and those heroes alive,'' said <PERSON> Kertzer </PERSON>, author of the recent `` Ritual, Politics and Power.'' Even if many Americans see <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s Birthday as just a chance for a three-day weekend, it still does its cultural job, said <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, professor of anthropology and urban studies at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION>. `` A good ritual does not have to have many participants to work, and they do n't have to be enthusiastic,'' she said. `` Have you ever been to a funeral in which you were secretly cheering?'' The important thing is that somebody observes the ritual, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. `` Our personal feelings about this are totally immaterial. These structures existed before we were born, and they will continue after we are dead.'' The holiday is observed more directly in schools, where it instructs the young, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON>, sociology professor at <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. So what does <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> represent? There's honesty, as in the cherry tree confession, and strength, as in flinging the silver dollar across the <LOCATION> Potomac </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. He also is portrayed as a loving and caring father of the country. `` People need fathers. This is a myth about how fathers should act,'' said <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, adding that the Valley Forge legend provides a classic hero myth. `` Heroes must go through a time of testing, in which they must triumph. They have to have followers and they have to have a sort of vision, even if it's not shared at the time with other people, of what they're doing.'' People `` want to know <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> could n't get supplies from the <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and is n't that typical? The vision of great leaders is not shared by the legislature. This is sort of a basic American myth about what kind of society do we have, and how did it come into being.'' Yet <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is the statesman with the formal wig as well as the revolutionary leader, said <PERSON> Kertzer </PERSON>. `` You do n't think of a heated personality, sort of a rabble rouser'' like <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>. By remembering <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> as a statesman-revolutionary, `` we deal with the ambiguity of our notion of a nation that was born with revolution, and yet a nation that is very conservative.'' For that purpose, he said, `` <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s perfect.''
</TEXT>
