<HEAD>Jet Propulsion Laboratory Produces Mars Movie</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> scientists have created an animated three-dimensional movie of Mars, seen from the view of an astronaut flying at 160,000 mph through the planet's canyons and above its volcanoes. `` Mars the Movie'' lasts about two minutes, and its simulated flight ranges from three miles to 500 miles above the surface of the red planet. The film `` takes the viewer on a tour through <PERSON> Valles </PERSON> <PERSON> Marineris </PERSON>, a canyon system near the Martian equator that stretches farther than the distance from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, and over <LOCATION> Tharsis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Montes </LOCATION>, a series of giant volcanoes more than twice the size of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Everest </LOCATION>,'' the space agency said. The movie was made by image-processing scientists at <ORGANIZATION> Jet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Propulsion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>, which runs <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s unmanned space exploration program for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. It uses computer-enhanced images taken by the Viking Orbiter spacecraft, and was designed to give scientists a more complete view of Earth's neighbor and to demonstrate improvements in the lab's ability to render 3-D images Production required 37 days of uninterrupted computer time, or 15 minutes for each of the film's more than 3,500 frames.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Drug Promising For Non-Surgical Treatment Of Enlarged Prostate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A drug used to combat high blood pressure shows promise as an alternative to surgery for treating prostate enlargement that afflicts up to 4 million <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> men, a scientist says. The prostate gland surrounds the neck of the bladder and the urethra in men, and manufactures part of the fluid in semen. For unknown reasons, it gradually enlarges after age 35; most men develop symptoms if they live long enough, said Dr. <PERSON> Perinchery </PERSON> <PERSON> Narayan </PERSON>, chief of urology at the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. Two million to 4 million men suffer prostate enlargement to the point that the gland squeezes the urethra to impede urine flow from the bladder, <PERSON> Narayan </PERSON> said. Symptoms range from frequent urination and burning sensations to infections, urine retention and life-threatening kidney failure. A preliminary study of 22 men found that four weeks of treatment with the drug terazosin provided 30 percent to 50 percent improvement in urine flow, he said. `` It looks like there's enough relief that our patients can avoid surgery. Whether this is permanent remains to be seen.'' Terazosin is used to treat high blood pressure because it relaxes smooth muscle in blood vessels. Researchers believe it has the same effect on smooth muscle in the urinary tract, opening the urethra despite the enlarged prostate. The drug does n't appear to reduce the size of the enlarged gland. The <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, plan to try terazosin on more 50 - to 75-year-old men with enlarged prostates Other scientists in the nationwide study are at <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin-Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tulane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Veterinarians Provide `Well-Cow Care' Through HMOOOOOOOOOOOOO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dairy cows are getting prepaid medical care under a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> program modeled on health maintenance organizations. `` In the past, veterinarians have been thought of as people who provide individual animal medicine or emergency care,'' said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitmore </PERSON>, head of food animal medicine and surgery at the university's College of Veterinary Medicine. `` But this is a new program to broaden the use and role of the veterinarian in the animal industry.'' For a fixed monthly fee based on herd size, the college provides all medical services, including hospitalization when needed and routine biweekly visits university spokesman <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> called `` well-cow care.'' The program helps owners keep medical costs under control, allows the veterinarians to influence cattle management and use a variety of skills, and also provides veterinary students with valuable experience. `` We study them as they grow and monitor them all the way through so we raise these animals efficiently, grow them at the right rate, breed them at the right time, calve them at the right time and manage for maximum milk production and profit,'' <PERSON> Whitmore </PERSON> said. `` The veterinarian wants to be viewed as a herd health consultant, not just a person who delivers emergency care.''
