<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some shopping pointers to keep in mind if you're 5-feet-4 or less and prefer not to dress like someone's little girl: Study your proportions If you have a long torso and short legs, choose long skirts and shoes with heels. If you have a short torso and long legs, then pick something like a long tunic to make the waist appear longer. The idea is to visually soften and blend the proportions. A key fitting point is at the shoulders. Collars and necklines should n't bunch up. Alterations are simpler for other parts of the garment if you start with a proportional shoulder fit. Choose softer versions of classically tailored suits. The details should be scaled down, with narrowed lapels and one-button closures. Jackets cut at hipbone length will look most natural with a smaller frame. Shoulder pads make the waist look smaller by extending the line of the shoulders, but make sure they're not too big and bulky. Horizontal lines will make you look chunky. So avoid square necklines or horizontal stripes or seams. By contrast, verticals _ V-necks, vertical stripes and seams _ will smooth and narrow your lines. Let color help, too. Monochromatic colors will help you maintain an unbroken visual line. You could match hosiery and pumps to solid colors in pants or skirts. Keep your accessories in proportion. Pass up wide belts and overlarge handbags -LRB- use your briefcase to transport extra items -RRB-. Shoes with medium heels will look best; avoid the extremes of stilletos or flats. Avoid fussy or cute touches, like <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Pan </PERSON> collars, puffed sleeves, big bows or ruffles, or extravagant costume jewelry. Stand up and be confident. Good posture and self-assurance has a lot to do with how well you look in your clothes. -LRB- The tips come from the Crafted with <ORGANIZATION> Pride </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which represents about 400 manufacturers. -RRB-
</TEXT>
