<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanborn </PERSON>, chairman, president and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, has died at the age of 52. <PERSON> Sanborn </PERSON> died Sunday afternoon of an apparent heart attack, said <PERSON> Sol </PERSON> <PERSON> Renick </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Philadelphia-based rail company. The board of directors will meet Wednesday to discuss a successor, the company said. <PERSON> Sanborn </PERSON>, who had 27 years of experience in the railroad business, took over as chairman on Jan. 1 with the retirement of <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Crane </PERSON>, who in eight years guided the company from massive losses to profitability. <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> was formed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1976 to reorganize six bankrupt Northeast railroads, including the <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION>. After 11 years of government ownership, <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> was sold March 26, 1987, for $ 1.6 billion in the largest public stock offering in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION>'s board elected <PERSON> Sanborn </PERSON> president and chief operating officer when <PERSON> Crane </PERSON> announced his retirement a year ago. Before joining <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Sanborn </PERSON> was president and CEO for <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Distribution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a unit of the railroad holding company <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. After graduating from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in 1960, <PERSON> Sanborn </PERSON> began his