<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Widens In January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus rose in January over a year ago as low oil prices continued to keep down import costs, the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. The surplus grew to $ 3.25 billion last month from $ 3.07 billion in January 1988, but was well below the monthly record of $ 9.65 billion set in December. January exports rose 11.5 percent from a year earlier to $ 19.32 billion and imports climbed 12.7 percent to $ 16.07 billion. The figures are compiled as the goods pass through customs. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, however, fell slightly over a year ago, to $ 2.974 billion from $ 2.976 billion. Exports to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market increased 11.1 percent to $ 6.50 billion, while imports from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> surged 22.4 percent to $ 3.52 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s overall surplus rose because of steady demand for Japanese goods in other countries enjoying continued economic expansion and because of lower prices for the crude oil <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> imports. They said imports of manufactured goods remain strong, a trend they expect to continue for some time. In trade with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> boosted car exports by 9.7 percent to $ 1.50 billion in January. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel sales in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> soared six-fold to $ 41.19 million and car sales nearly doubled to $ 41.62 million. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s exports to the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> rose 6.4 percent to $ 3.66 billion in January, while imports from the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> leaped 24.4 percent to $ 2.02 billion. That left <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> with a surplus of $ 1.64 billion, down from $ 1.82 billion in January 1988. Because of large oil imports, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> ran a $ 1.04 billion deficit in trade with the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, down from $ 1.30 billion in January 1988.
