<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 2026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv14   02-13 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 14,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tues., Feb. 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>Interest Rate Shopping Pays _ Over and Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The same people who eagerly seek rebates of a few hundred dollars on new-car purchases or wait in line at appliance store sales could be tossing away tens of thousands of dollars on their <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> accounts. It is being done every day, casually and indifferently, by thousands of individuals who -LRB- 1 -RRB- fail to shop for the best rates, which now vary widely, and -LRB- 2 -RRB- fail to comprehend the impact of compounding over extended time periods. Adding to the waste and confusion is institutional ignorance of their own products, according to <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mintz </PERSON>, an analyst and critic of insurance and financial practices. In a check of 13 institutions in the first week of February, he found only a couple that could even estimate the total a certain deposit amount would become over a specific time period. Three branches of the same bank gave different figures. After 34 years of dealing with the sale of insurance, annuities, certificates of deposit, <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>, retirement plans and the like, the soft-spoken, intense, <PERSON> Mintz </PERSON> believes consumers need factual point-of-sale information. In pursuit of his goal, he has testified before committees of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, offered his somewhat testy and often unwelcome views at insurance industry meetings and aided government agencies in studies of IRAs and insurance. He publishes the NROCA -LRB- `` acorn'' backwards -RRB- Newsletter _ Department C, <ORGANIZATION> NROCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, Box 12066, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> 75225. It seeks to give `` one or two ideas a year to retirees and preretirees that will be worth hundreds if not multi-thousands of dollars.'' <ORGANIZATION> NROCA </ORGANIZATION>'s most recent offering, at $ 8.75 a copy, is a `` Consumer's Guide to Compound Interest,'' providing 1,600 yields arranged to allow even financially unsophisticated individuals to analyze IRAs, insurance, CDs, and savings Though a thorn to financial and insurance institutions, <PERSON> Mintz </PERSON> remains in the mainstream, if barely. His views are heard if not welcomed. He authored a study course presented by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> of CPAs. He is on the editorial board of a professional, financially-oriented national magazine. Working with telephone and computer from his home, <PERSON> Mintz </PERSON> found published certificate of deposit yields ranging from 8.33 percent to 9.8 percent at institutions throughout the country during the first week of February. That difference in yields could mean that a $ 10,000 investment after 30 years might be worth $ 110,271 _ or $ 165,223. It would mean that a $ 2,000 deposit each year for 30 years could be worth $ 260,800 _ or $ 347,826. To his dismay, he found that while financial institutions quote precise interest rates, almost none can state accurately how much a deposit will total over a specific time period. That is, what the annual yield would be. Interest rates and yields differ, mainly because of compounding, which can be daily, monthly, quarterly, semiannually or annually. The differences seem small, but time magnifies them. Compounding, therefore, can be magic or tragic _ magic if you utilize it, tragic if you do n't. At an interest rate of 10 percent compounded annually, for example, $ 10,000 becomes $ 67,275 in 20 years. If compounded daily, the 10 percent rate totals $ 75,962, a yield of 10.67 percent a year. <PERSON> Mintz </PERSON> bases his conclusion _ that institutions can not calculate yields _ on the responses to his request for information on the placement with them of $ 87,000 in a rollover <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> for three or five years. His question: `` How much in cash can I withdraw without penalty at the end of the period? Also, give me the rate and yield.'' It was then, he says, that three branches of one bank gave answers ranging from $ 118,000 to $ 133,000 for the five-year period. And a bank that advertised quarterly compounding, he says, based calculations on 360 rather than 365 days. End Adv PMs Tues., Feb. 14.
</TEXT>
