<HEAD>Unit 3 World's Top Nuclear Power Plant Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINTERSBURG, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Palo Verde Unit 3 generated more electricty last year than any nuclear plant in the world, operators said Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION> said statistics from Nucleonics Week, a publication of the nuclear industry, show that the newest of three units at the generating station 50 miles west of <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> produced 10.87 million megawatt hours last year _ enough for two cities the size of <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>. The output of the plant's other two reactors lagged, however. According to <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> figures, Unit 1 has operated at 51 percent of capacity since its startup in late 1985, and Unit 2 has run at 67.3 percent. Unit 3, which was started in late 1987 and entered commercial operation early in 1988, has operated at nearly 90 percent of capacity and last summer set a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> record of 214 days of continuous operation after startup. It also set a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> record for a month, with 955,400 megawatts in March. Each of the triplet reactors is rated at 1,270 megawatts. <ORGANIZATION> ANPP </ORGANIZATION> officials said they serve 4 million customers of the seven utilities in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> which united to build the $ 9.3 billion complex. The publication listed the Grohnde and Philippsburg-2 nuclear plants in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> as Nos. 2 and 3 in the world, with 1988 production of 10.79 million and 10.21 million megawatts, respectively.
