<HEAD>School Endowment Performance Hurt by Stock Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 College and university endowments earned some money on their investments for fiscal 1988 but the performance was hurt by the stock market crash, a study reported Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Officers </ORGANIZATION> said that the average rate of return for the period July 1, 1987 to June 30, 1988 was 1.3 percent. That was down from 13.9 percent in fiscal 1987. `` Considering the year on the stock market, we were pleased that they had a positive rate of return,'' said association spokeswoman <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> <PERSON> Howton </PERSON>. She said the endowments held their own for a number of reasons. `` The best stocks did rebound after the crash,'' she said. `` And not all institutions are totally invested into stocks. Bonds and CDs did well.'' The endowment study of 315 schools, conducted annually since 1974, showed total market value for participating funds at $ 49.5 billion in fiscal 1988, up from $ 47.9 billion the previous year. The 10 participating institutions with the highest endowment fund assets were the same 10 as the year before, in the same order. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> topped the list with an endowment of nearly $ 4.2 billion, as of mid-1988. The <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> system was second with $ 2.8 billion, followed by <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> at $ 2.3 billion and <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> at $ 2.1 billion. The other top 10 institutions were <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION>, $ 1.6 billion; <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>, $ 1.4 billion; <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> 