o. </ORGANIZATION>, the No. 2 Japanese condom maker, and <ORGANIZATION> Nisshoiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, a Japanese trading company, own 60 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Safetex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Lyndhurst </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> under a joint venture begun in 1987. <PERSON> Fuji </PERSON> has made condoms in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since buying the <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> plant of <ORGANIZATION> Circle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> about 15 years ago, which it since has closed. <ORGANIZATION> Sagami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s Kimono condom has been imported by <ORGANIZATION> Mayer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, since April 1987. Industry analysts warn that the Japanese may have difficulty in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> condom market because Americans remain somewhat embarrassed by the subject. They therefore are likely to stay with brands they recognize and can grab quickly from store shelves. New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Carter-Wallace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, maker of the Trojans brand of condoms, now controls about 53 percent of the market. <ORGANIZATION> Schmid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, controls about 27 percent of the market with such brands as <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON>, Sheik and Excita. <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> predicts condom sales will continue growing at 15 percent annually in the foreseeable future. But some observers predict growth will slow with the calming of fears about heterosexual transmission of AIDS.
