<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> countries disagreed Monday on a proposed witholding tax of 15 percent on interest income from bonds and bank savings and sent the plan to a high-level study group. At a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> economics and finance ministers, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> completely opposed the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s proposal while <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> sought a reduction in toward the level of its own tax of 10 percent. Of the other member states, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> broadly supported the proposal. The proposal was made last week by the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in an effort to harmonize the widely different taxes on interest income in the 12 member States _ from zero in <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> to 35 percent in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. Because <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> laws on taxation need to be approved unanimously, diplomats said that it was difficult to see how the proposals could be adopted unless radical changes were made. <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>'s Finance Minister <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Poos </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> would block the commission's plan. <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, which has banking secrecy laws and is considered the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s tax haven, fears its economy will suffer if a tax is imposed. The high-level study group is expected to complete its report in four to six weeks. The ministers will discuss its conclusions at their regular monthly meeting in April. The group is composed of the chief tax authoritie