<HEAD>Champion Products Finds Friendly Buyer for $321 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSFORD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Champion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a maker of athletic and leisure clothing, successfully fought off a hostile takeover and agreed Monday to be sold to <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> Corp. of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> for $ 320.9 million. The announcement that the food and apparel giant would buy Champion for $ 77 a share followed Champion's request for bids to fend off a takeover by a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment group. `` Our shareholders are receiving full value and this transaction is the best possible outcome for our employees, customers and the communities in which we operate,'' Champion President <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> said. Champion, well-known in college bookstores around the country for sweatshirts and T-shirts, had been a takeover target of the investment group <ORGANIZATION> Walsh </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greenwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Acting through <ORGANIZATION> Phonicam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a company created to attempt the takeover, the investment group had offered $ 51 a share, $ 55 a share and last month upped its offer to $ 61 a share `` I think the $ 61 figure was getting into an area that shareholders may have started thinking they were getting fair value, and that's why management went looking for buyers,'' said <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Rayomnd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION>, Fla.-based borkerage firm. <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> officials said they would begin a tender offer this week for the 4.16 million outstanding shares of fully diluted Champion stock and various convertible stock options. Champion stock climbed $ 12.125 to close at $ 75.75 in <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading Monday. After the deal was announced, a spokesman for <PERSON> Phonicam </PERSON> said the company could n't justify spending that much money for Champion. <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said she thought the sale to <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> might help Champion continue its fast-paced growth because the company might receive more capital investment from its new parent. Champion has enjoyed 14 straight quarters of increased sales and profits, and last year boosted earnings 114 percent to $ 14.89 million, or $ 4.34 a share, on sales of $ 219 million. Although the company is best known for uniforms and athletic clothes, much of Champion's recent growth has come by adding leisure wear and branching out into department and specialty stores. <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, one of the nation's 50 largest companies, sells packaged food and various consumer products and operates a food service business. The company reported $ 10.4 billion in sales in its last fiscal year. `` One of our missions is to grow all of our businesses, and strategic acquisition is one way of doing that,'' <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Culp </PERSON> said. `` This was just one of those good opportunities that come along.'' <PERSON> Culp </PERSON> said the company had not been interested in buying Champion until it was asked to make a bid for the suburban Rochester-based firm. Champion will join <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s other apparel companies, including Hanes underwear, L'eggs hosiery, Isotoner gloves and <LOCATION> Bali </LOCATION> bras.
