<HEAD>Barbie and G.I. Joe: Survivors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after the 6th, ``But quality,'' to UPDATE with
toy maker's comments on another toy failure, add Monday time element.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Barbie and G.I. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> had birthday parties this week. Mr. Game Show could n't make it. `` He died,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirchberger </PERSON>, a toy company analyst. Weep not, though, for Mr. <PERSON> Show </PERSON>. Of the estimated 5,000 games and toys being introduced at the toy industry's annual coming-out party in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> this week, the vast majority will join him in that big toybox in the sky. `` You'll see a lot of products at the Toy Fair this week that you wo n't see next year,'' said <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON>, another industry analyst. `` Most toys do not make it into a second season.'' One reason: `` There's lots of junk.'' But quality is n't the only criterion; some entries are undone only by outrageous circumstance. `` The Evel Knievel doll did very well when it came out. Then it just fell apart,'' said <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. He guessed that <PERSON> Knievel </PERSON>'s 1977 guilty plea in a baseball-bat assault did n't help the toy. Plain poor judgment kills other entries. Consider the ill-starred Golden Girl and the Guardian of the Gemstones. `` One of the biggest stiffs in the history of the business,'' its manufacturer, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Galoob </PERSON>, said Monday. `` The concept was action figures for little girls,'' said <PERSON> Galoob </PERSON>, chief of <ORGANIZATION> Lewis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Galoob </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` There were 12 beautiful female warriors with shields and swords. The trade bought in very, very heavily. `` And what we discovered was that little girls did n't want to play with warrior figurines.'' Other casualties of the toy wars are harder to explain. Barbie turns 30 years old this week, dancing on the grave of a pretender named Gem. While G.I. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> marches on at 25, the Inhumanoids _ a toady group from the center of the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> _ withered in the light of day. Why? Nobody knows. `` That is the $ 64 million question in the toy industry. And in most other industries,'' said <PERSON> Kirchberger </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Paine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Webber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` Nobody sets out to make a bad movie. It just happens. It's the same thing with toys. Manufacturers are willing to enter the fray in hopes of capturing a chunk of the $ 12.8 billion annual toy business. They trim losses by making models of most new toys, holding back on full-scale production until orders come in. Still, there have been some epic bombs. <ORGANIZATION> View-Master </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ideal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is still scratching its head over <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s Zoo, a menagerie of stuffed animals inspired by the rock star's predilection for offbeat pets `` He even went on tour with his chimp. So we tried,'' said View-Master's <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON>. `` We had the chimp appearing in stores in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. We had quite a few good promotions, but we just could n't move the product.'' Then there was Mr. Game Show, a big hit at last year's Toy Fair, a goner now. <PERSON> Kirchberger </PERSON> gave the eulogy: `` It was modeled after a TV game show; there was a figure of a host, he spoke, he'd ask you questions, you'd push buttons to indicate your answer, he'd tell you if you were right or wrong and how much you won. `` Very clever. Wrong price point, wrong I-don ` Mr. Game Show did n't make it.''
