<HEAD>Dollar Ends Lower; Gold Declines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar finished lower against most major currencies Monday in thin trading as players awaited the next round of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic reports. Gold prices also declined. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold bullion was bid at $ 385.20 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $ 387 late Friday. The dollar advanced in the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and continued rising later in European trading, buoyed by expectations of higher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates. The dollar later retreated in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Dealers said last Friday's report of a greater-than-expected 1 percent rise in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wholesale prices in January had rekindled speculation that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> would hike its discount rate soon in an effort to help curb inflation by slowing the economy. But the absence of a rate boost took away the market's excuse to drive the dollar still higher, traders said. The discount rate is the interest the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> charges on loans to financial institutions. `` We did n't see a lot of business moving through today,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON>, vice president of corporate currency trading at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office of <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. `` It's a case of a market that's waiting for additional economic data before it moves.'' Market participants are awaiting the publication of Tuesday's report on retail sales for January, Wednesday's report on business inventories and factory use for December, Thursday's report on January housing starts and Friday's report on the December merchandise trade deficit In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.65 Japanese yen to a closing 128.30 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 128.60 yen and by the end of trading in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar was quoted at 128.07 yen, down from 128.68 yen late Friday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fell to $ 1.7495 from $ 1.7547 on Friday. Later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, sterling advanced to $ 1.7525 from $ 1.7467 late Friday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Friday's rates, included: 1.8677 West German marks, down from 1.8695; 1.5877 Swiss francs, down from 1.5885; 6.3575 French francs, down from 6.3588; 1,359.00 Italian lire, down from 1,363.50; and 1.1860 Canadian dollars, unchanged Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Friday's rates, included: 1.8705 West German marks, up from 1.8595; 1.5895 Swiss francs, up from 1.5778; 6.3650 French francs, up from 6.3200; 2.1120 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0960; 1,362.50 Italian lire, up from 1,353.75; and 1.1868 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1857 Gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid of $ 384.25 a troy ounce from $ 391 bid late Friday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the late bid for gold was $ 383.75, down from $ 389.50 bid late Friday. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 6.80 an ounce to close at a bid of $ 387.05. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold for current delivery declined to $ 386.20 a troy ounce from $ 388.80 late Friday. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid of $ 5.79 a troy ounce, down from Friday's late bid of $ 5.85. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver for current delivery rose to $ 5.826 a troy ounce from $ 5.812 late Friday.
