<HEAD>Security Forces Remove Strikers from Steel Mill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Security agents at a steel mill evicted several hundred strikers Monday to stop them from harassing people who continued working, official media and sources in the area reported. At least 1,000 people, most of them blast-furnace workers, walked off their jobs Sunday at the mill in <LOCATION> Zenica </LOCATION>. They demanded double wages for January compared with December, higher wages for night work and other special payments because of inflation now at an annual rate of about 300 percent. Several hundred <LOCATION> Zenica </LOCATION> workers marched to the town hall Sunday to press their demands. <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION>, the official news agency, said `` the mill's security forces evicted ... several hundred'' strikers Monday evening who were involved in minor skirmishes with people who stayed on the job. Its report was brief and did not say whether anyone was injured. It was believed to be the first such action by factory authorities in communist <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. Sources said on condition of anonymity that no one was seriously injured. They said security men `` literally pushed the strikers out of the factory gates.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said mill authorities responded to `` the improper and rowdy behavior of some strikers which endangered the security of the people and the installations at the mill.'' The agency said the situation in the plant 90 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> became `` volatile'' when management announced Monday afternoon that it would not give in to the strikers' demands, <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> television said the factory produced 400 tons of steel less on Monday than in a usual day. It also showed some of the skirmishes between strikers and workers. About 22,000 people work at the mill, which was built after World War II and served as a symbol of communist industrial development until it began losing money in recent years. Nearly 2,000 strikes were reported in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> last year, most of them to protest lower living standards brought about by the nation's severe economic problems.
