<HEAD>Market Indicates Semiconductor Demand Increasing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Market figures for January indicate semiconductor demand is increasing for the first time in four months and that the contracting market may be slightly reversing itself, analysts said Monday. An increase in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> semiconductor orders caused a rise in the closely watched `` book-to-bill'' ratio for January, which reached 1.0, according to figures released by the <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The figure was .93 in December. A book-to-bill ratio of 1.0 means that for every $ 100 worth of products billed, manufacturers received $ 100 worth of new orders, or bookings. The total shipments, or billings, of $ 1.004 million in January were 10.9 percent higher than the same figure a year ago and 17.1 percent lower than in December. The January 1989 orders, or bookings, of $ 1.124 million were 5.8 percent higher than the average bookings posted last year and 5.4 percent higher than December's figure. `` It means the industry is coming back toward a growth environment after four months with less than a one-to-one -LRB- ratio -RRB-, indicating a shrinking of the market and people buying less from September to now,'' said <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelps </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> Hambrecht </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Quist investment company. `` This indicates for the first time they are beginning to order as much as is being produced,'' he said.
